00:00:43.600 --> 00:00:48.710
So now just a quick bit about
lesson planning, because a

00:00:48.710 --> 00:00:51.410
couple of you pointed out that
you'd have liked to know more

00:00:51.410 --> 00:00:53.070
about lesson planning.

00:00:53.070 --> 00:00:57.470
And reminded me that when I
taught the chemistry TA

00:00:57.470 --> 00:01:02.580
workshops, I actually gave
everyone a handout on how to

00:01:02.580 --> 00:01:03.610
plan a lesson.

00:01:03.610 --> 00:01:07.020
So I've put that handout online,
and I'll just show you

00:01:07.020 --> 00:01:08.270
what it looks like here.

00:01:24.900 --> 00:01:28.920
So this is basically the sheet I
use for planning any kind of

00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:32.370
lecture recitation.

00:01:32.370 --> 00:01:39.240
At the top, you need some kind
of course, and date.

00:01:39.240 --> 00:01:44.360
And then the objective.

00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:46.880
So that's quite important.

00:01:46.880 --> 00:01:48.010
You'll see the exact sheet.

00:01:48.010 --> 00:01:51.220
And there's a PDF file, you
can just use it yourself.

00:01:51.220 --> 00:01:56.420
There's a course objective for
that particular session.

00:01:56.420 --> 00:01:58.850
And that relates to your overall
goals for the course.

00:01:58.850 --> 00:02:02.270
So, for example, in this
problem, my objective might be

00:02:02.270 --> 00:02:07.420
something like, to show
that easy cases--

00:02:07.420 --> 00:02:09.060
in fact, this was
my objective--

00:02:09.060 --> 00:02:11.130
I wanted to show that
easy cases--

00:02:11.130 --> 00:02:14.060
extreme cases-- are useful not
just for checking formulas,

00:02:14.060 --> 00:02:15.385
but also for generating
formulas.

00:02:26.490 --> 00:02:28.760
OK, so I write that
on the top.

00:02:28.760 --> 00:02:30.930
So I remind myself,
why am I here?

00:02:30.930 --> 00:02:32.180
What am I doing?

00:02:34.390 --> 00:02:37.930
Then there's a three-column
table.

00:02:37.930 --> 00:02:40.660
Basically you just plan
items in your lecture.

00:02:43.580 --> 00:02:45.440
The first column is minutes--

00:02:45.440 --> 00:02:47.660
how long you expect each
thing to take.

00:02:47.660 --> 00:02:57.000
And then the middle column, most
of the space is, what's

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:00.740
your goal in this local
part of the lecture?

00:03:00.740 --> 00:03:02.390
And what are you going
to do for that?

00:03:02.390 --> 00:03:04.910
So here's my overall
objective.

00:03:04.910 --> 00:03:08.130
And my local goal may be,
just this example--

00:03:08.130 --> 00:03:11.180
getting that one third.

00:03:11.180 --> 00:03:16.770
And then here in the third
column is props.

00:03:16.770 --> 00:03:20.610
So there's actually
a piece here, too.

00:03:20.610 --> 00:03:23.040
So props are anything that
I need to bring.

00:03:23.040 --> 00:03:24.590
So I just stick that
in the margin.

00:03:24.590 --> 00:03:27.350
OK, bring the cones,
or the pyramids,

00:03:27.350 --> 00:03:28.630
whatever they may be.

00:03:28.630 --> 00:03:32.150
And so then, when you're filling
this piece in, about

00:03:32.150 --> 00:03:36.570
what to bring, you just scan
down this last column, and

00:03:36.570 --> 00:03:38.630
just write everything here.

00:03:38.630 --> 00:03:40.330
OK, cones.

00:03:40.330 --> 00:03:44.080
Homework three, solution set
two-- whatever it may be.

00:03:44.080 --> 00:03:49.310
So now, at a glance, before you
go to your session, you

00:03:49.310 --> 00:03:51.020
review these two things.

00:03:51.020 --> 00:03:53.500
Make sure you have everything,
your know why you're here.

00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:56.270
But then here, you're going
to follow your script.

00:03:56.270 --> 00:03:57.590
Which is a loose script.

00:03:57.590 --> 00:03:59.830
It's not exactly a word-for-word
script.

00:03:59.830 --> 00:04:02.400
It's, maybe, a few equations.

00:04:02.400 --> 00:04:03.650
Suppose there's a question.

00:04:06.860 --> 00:04:10.250
What is this constant?

00:04:10.250 --> 00:04:12.900
OK, so that's my overall,
what I'm going to do

00:04:12.900 --> 00:04:15.600
for, say, ten minutes.

00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:19.079
And then I break it into
sub-questions.

00:04:19.079 --> 00:04:20.329
OK.

00:04:23.540 --> 00:04:25.000
What is H and B?

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:26.620
How many pyramids do I need?

00:04:26.620 --> 00:04:27.740
What's my goal shape?

00:04:27.740 --> 00:04:29.510
So these are questions
that I ask students.

00:04:29.510 --> 00:04:32.330
And for each one, I write
down the minutes.

00:04:32.330 --> 00:04:36.170
Maybe in parentheses, put
the total up here.

00:04:36.170 --> 00:04:39.630
So now, when I've done my two
or three pages-- and by the

00:04:39.630 --> 00:04:43.900
way I find, just at the level of
detail I use, if I ever go

00:04:43.900 --> 00:04:47.810
beyond three pages, I never
get to that material.

00:04:47.810 --> 00:04:50.950
So it's just sort of for a
security blanket by the time

00:04:50.950 --> 00:04:53.010
I'm beyond three pages.

00:04:53.010 --> 00:04:55.330
It depends how detailed you
write these things, but I've

00:04:55.330 --> 00:04:58.140
generally found that's
where I am.

00:04:58.140 --> 00:05:00.155
And then, you estimate
the time.

00:05:00.155 --> 00:05:02.120
And what you'll find is, the
first time you do stuff,

00:05:02.120 --> 00:05:04.300
you'll massively underestimate
the time.

00:05:04.300 --> 00:05:06.960
You'll be off by a
factor of two.

00:05:06.960 --> 00:05:10.070
So, in other words, if you think
it takes five minutes,

00:05:10.070 --> 00:05:11.800
it'll really take ten minutes.

00:05:11.800 --> 00:05:14.810
And that's true even after you
take account of this rule.

00:05:14.810 --> 00:05:17.620
Sort of.

00:05:17.620 --> 00:05:20.970
OK, so then you put down all
your minutes on this page, and

00:05:20.970 --> 00:05:21.470
the next page.

00:05:21.470 --> 00:05:24.720
You add them up, and you make
sure that you're not over 50,

00:05:24.720 --> 00:05:25.980
or whatever the amount is.

00:05:25.980 --> 00:05:30.200
And then what you'll find is
what you thought was 50 really

00:05:30.200 --> 00:05:32.150
is going to take you 130.

00:05:32.150 --> 00:05:34.980
So the next time, when you
evaluate minutes, you'll have

00:05:34.980 --> 00:05:35.680
a better idea.

00:05:35.680 --> 00:05:38.220
And you'll find yourself
actually tuning your time

00:05:38.220 --> 00:05:40.490
sense pretty well.

00:05:40.490 --> 00:05:44.580
So now I've got my time sense
that I don't really need to

00:05:44.580 --> 00:05:47.580
put the minutes down, because
I can just do it

00:05:47.580 --> 00:05:49.380
by number of pages.

00:05:49.380 --> 00:05:50.810
Three pages, too much.

00:05:50.810 --> 00:05:54.960
And so you'll find your own
writing level, and detail

00:05:54.960 --> 00:05:56.870
level, how many pages to use.

00:05:56.870 --> 00:05:59.560
Now the other point is, where do
these questions come from?

00:05:59.560 --> 00:06:03.760
OK, well this is a way you can
turn any regular lecture into

00:06:03.760 --> 00:06:04.900
an interactive one.

00:06:04.900 --> 00:06:06.560
So suppose you have a
long derivation that

00:06:06.560 --> 00:06:07.140
you're going to do.

00:06:07.140 --> 00:06:11.570
Or, for example, suppose the
first way I planned this, was

00:06:11.570 --> 00:06:14.170
I wanted to show people that
this was 1/3 over here, this

00:06:14.170 --> 00:06:15.680
is three here.

00:06:15.680 --> 00:06:17.950
And the way I was going to do
it, was I was going to draw

00:06:17.950 --> 00:06:21.900
six pyramids, show them in a
cube, and show that 6V, and do

00:06:21.900 --> 00:06:22.970
all this showing.

00:06:22.970 --> 00:06:27.570
Well, first draft, write it all
out like that, with times

00:06:27.570 --> 00:06:29.570
and everything, without
questions.

00:06:29.570 --> 00:06:33.230
Then, any time you come to
something interesting--

00:06:33.230 --> 00:06:34.480
so here.

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:43.075
So before you have [? tel. ?]

00:06:48.500 --> 00:06:52.430
So now you look at your sheet,
and you say, hmm, where did

00:06:52.430 --> 00:06:53.930
something interesting happen?

00:06:53.930 --> 00:06:56.940
Hopefully, there is at
least one point.

00:06:56.940 --> 00:06:58.950
Because if there isn't, maybe
you shouldn't be giving the

00:06:58.950 --> 00:07:00.400
lecture at all.

00:07:00.400 --> 00:07:03.280
So now, let's just say, by
construction, you found some

00:07:03.280 --> 00:07:04.030
interesting things.

00:07:04.030 --> 00:07:05.700
OK, so that's interesting.

00:07:05.700 --> 00:07:07.800
Oh, it's interesting that
it makes a cube--

00:07:07.800 --> 00:07:09.800
it's not obvious.

00:07:09.800 --> 00:07:13.300
So just think, where does
something require thought, and

00:07:13.300 --> 00:07:16.220
that you're short-circuiting
the thought by telling.

00:07:16.220 --> 00:07:20.980
So then, what I do is I have a
green pen, and I turn it into

00:07:20.980 --> 00:07:22.310
a question.

00:07:22.310 --> 00:07:27.710
So I'll circle it in green, and
write, "ask" next to it.

00:07:27.710 --> 00:07:29.800
OK, or you can just rewrite
your sheet.

00:07:38.170 --> 00:07:42.470
Telling something, then asking,
and then continuing.

00:07:42.470 --> 00:07:45.190
OK so that's how you can turn
any regular lecture into an

00:07:45.190 --> 00:07:46.170
interactive one.

00:07:46.170 --> 00:07:49.470
And that's your sheet that
you walk into class with.

00:07:49.470 --> 00:07:51.860
And what you'll find, is that
the first time you do it that

00:07:51.860 --> 00:07:54.900
way, there will be a bunch more
spots you realize were

00:07:54.900 --> 00:07:55.680
actually subtle.

00:07:55.680 --> 00:07:59.250
Because, for example, at the end
of class session, when you

00:07:59.250 --> 00:08:01.110
collect your feedback sheets,
people will have questions

00:08:01.110 --> 00:08:01.830
about different parts.

00:08:01.830 --> 00:08:04.290
You'll realize, oh, there was
actually something interesting

00:08:04.290 --> 00:08:06.000
that happened that wasn't
obvious in one of these

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:06.980
telling points.

00:08:06.980 --> 00:08:10.880
And you'll be able to turn that
into a question, as well.

00:08:10.880 --> 00:08:15.360
The master sheet with all that
formatted for you is online,

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:16.710
on the course website.

00:08:16.710 --> 00:08:18.970
And you're welcome to use that
in your own teaching, and

00:08:18.970 --> 00:08:22.280
distribute it to everyone you
know Any questions about that?

00:08:25.490 --> 00:08:25.810
Yes.

00:08:25.810 --> 00:08:28.270
AUDIENCE: When you run over
time, then you have to shift

00:08:28.270 --> 00:08:29.668
some of the things to
the next lecture.

00:08:29.668 --> 00:08:32.520
So how do you do that?

00:08:32.520 --> 00:08:35.289
PROFESSOR: What happens when
you run over time.

00:08:35.289 --> 00:08:37.669
The first time you teach the
course, you basically find out

00:08:37.669 --> 00:08:39.714
there's just twice as much
material in the course as

00:08:39.714 --> 00:08:40.669
there should be.

00:08:40.669 --> 00:08:42.940
And you'll always be running
over time if you try to cover

00:08:42.940 --> 00:08:45.060
every single thing.

00:08:45.060 --> 00:08:48.080
So, the first time you
run out of time--

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:49.160
there's two approaches to it.

00:08:49.160 --> 00:08:55.290
One is just to slow the entire
pace down, and cover half of

00:08:55.290 --> 00:08:56.280
the amount of material.

00:08:56.280 --> 00:08:58.400
So that's quite a reasonable
approach.

00:08:58.400 --> 00:09:01.170
The other is to sort of keep
rhythm, but not cover every

00:09:01.170 --> 00:09:01.870
single thing.

00:09:01.870 --> 00:09:04.480
So my piano teacher, a while
ago, she said, when you're

00:09:04.480 --> 00:09:07.310
sight-reading new piano music,
the most important thing is,

00:09:07.310 --> 00:09:08.090
keep rhythm.

00:09:08.090 --> 00:09:11.310
So don't just stop, and then
think for like ten seconds

00:09:11.310 --> 00:09:13.050
about one measure, and
then continue in

00:09:13.050 --> 00:09:14.220
this herk and jerk.

00:09:14.220 --> 00:09:17.280
Just keep playing at speed, but
skip some of the notes,

00:09:17.280 --> 00:09:18.910
and do whatever you have
to do to keep rhythm.

00:09:18.910 --> 00:09:21.880
So you can try that
approach too.

00:09:21.880 --> 00:09:24.340
And then, what you do is you
say, OK look I'm not going to

00:09:24.340 --> 00:09:25.850
cover every single
thing in lecture.

00:09:25.850 --> 00:09:28.070
A lot of stuff is in the book.

00:09:28.070 --> 00:09:29.680
And that's good to do anyway.

00:09:29.680 --> 00:09:32.910
So a mix of the two approaches
is one way to deal with

00:09:32.910 --> 00:09:34.120
running over time.

00:09:34.120 --> 00:09:34.610
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:09:34.610 --> 00:09:37.250
So each lecture you have
some objective.

00:09:37.250 --> 00:09:40.410
And then, if you run over
time, then in the first

00:09:40.410 --> 00:09:41.850
lecture, you only finish
half of it.

00:09:41.850 --> 00:09:44.812
And then, the second one seems
to start from the middle of

00:09:44.812 --> 00:09:46.780
[INAUDIBLE].

00:09:46.780 --> 00:09:48.740
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:09:48.740 --> 00:09:48.970
OK.

00:09:48.970 --> 00:09:50.590
So that's one reason
it's worth writing

00:09:50.590 --> 00:09:52.160
the objective first.

00:09:52.160 --> 00:09:53.750
Because then you know what
the main goal is.

00:09:53.750 --> 00:09:56.330
So one way to do it,
which I do like, is

00:09:56.330 --> 00:09:58.110
to make sure that--

00:09:58.110 --> 00:10:00.710
right away-- the objective
is reached.

00:10:00.710 --> 00:10:03.040
So you do it as sort
of a layer cake.

00:10:03.040 --> 00:10:04.510
So the first example--

00:10:04.510 --> 00:10:06.640
maybe the first two examples--

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:09.750
just from those, if everybody
just doesn't do anything else

00:10:09.750 --> 00:10:11.920
but the first two examples,
which you expect will only

00:10:11.920 --> 00:10:13.030
take 15 minutes--

00:10:13.030 --> 00:10:15.320
but it takes 40 minutes,
it's okay.

00:10:15.320 --> 00:10:18.620
Because the first two examples
reach your objective.

00:10:18.620 --> 00:10:21.130
Now they don't reach the
objective 100%, but they give

00:10:21.130 --> 00:10:22.810
you 80% of the objective.

00:10:22.810 --> 00:10:26.430
So you want to plan your lecture
structure like a layer

00:10:26.430 --> 00:10:30.670
cake, or like JPEG.

00:10:30.670 --> 00:10:32.790
People know how JPEG
compression works?

00:10:32.790 --> 00:10:38.390
So JPEG, the way you do it, is
the low-frequency, quote,

00:10:38.390 --> 00:10:41.090
"most important" terms,
come first.

00:10:41.090 --> 00:10:44.470
And then the higher-frequency,
say, less important terms,

00:10:44.470 --> 00:10:45.060
come later.

00:10:45.060 --> 00:10:47.810
So sometimes you see things
rendered in your browser

00:10:47.810 --> 00:10:50.660
step-by-step, and they just
sort of take focus.

00:10:50.660 --> 00:10:53.960
And it gets better and better as
you wait longer and longer.

00:10:53.960 --> 00:10:56.050
So you want to plan your
lecture a bit that way.

00:10:56.050 --> 00:10:58.970
So that it's robust
to time shortage.

00:10:58.970 --> 00:11:01.850
So that if, for example, there's
a fire alarm halfway

00:11:01.850 --> 00:11:04.480
through your lecture, still
the main point got across.

00:11:04.480 --> 00:11:06.740
Now it didn't get across in
all the detail, and the

00:11:06.740 --> 00:11:09.840
beautiful glory of that you
wanted, but the main point

00:11:09.840 --> 00:11:11.480
still got across.

00:11:11.480 --> 00:11:14.000
So then, if you run out
of time, it's OK.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.330
You say, look, there's two more
examples of this which we

00:11:16.330 --> 00:11:19.190
didn't do, but they further
illustrate the main point.

00:11:19.190 --> 00:11:21.420
See the notes.

00:11:21.420 --> 00:11:23.990
And then you can keep
to your plan.

00:11:23.990 --> 00:11:25.740
Assuming that your plan
is a reasonable one.

00:11:25.740 --> 00:11:28.480
If your plan is that, I'm going
to do f equals ma today,

00:11:28.480 --> 00:11:33.130
and I'm going to do rigid body
rotation tomorrow, that's

00:11:33.130 --> 00:11:34.610
probably not a reasonable
plan.

00:11:34.610 --> 00:11:36.695
And the fact that you ran out of
time on day one is probably

00:11:36.695 --> 00:11:39.690
a good sign that you should
actually spend a little more

00:11:39.690 --> 00:11:41.840
time on f equals ma.

00:11:41.840 --> 00:11:43.880
Does that answer
your question?

00:11:43.880 --> 00:11:45.980
Other questions?

00:11:45.980 --> 00:11:47.308
Yes.

