The zero-th order term is
that, if you can't help

00:12:58.550 --> 00:13:02.880
yourself, use slides, but
otherwise, use blackboard.

00:13:02.880 --> 00:13:08.260
For 90% of things, blackboard
is much better for teaching

00:13:08.260 --> 00:13:10.120
than slides.

00:13:10.120 --> 00:13:12.820
There are some cases where
slides are useful, and you can

00:13:12.820 --> 00:13:13.890
make an argument for it.

00:13:13.890 --> 00:13:16.920
There's some cases where maybe
the slide is as good as a

00:13:16.920 --> 00:13:19.700
blackboard, few cases where it's
better than a blackboard.

00:13:19.700 --> 00:13:22.220
But the default is, blackboards

00:13:22.220 --> 00:13:24.790
are better than slides.

00:13:24.790 --> 00:13:28.255
Now let me show you an example
of why that's true.

00:13:33.070 --> 00:13:35.170
Suppose you're teaching the--

00:13:35.170 --> 00:13:37.760
an example I've done with you
before, slightly, is the

00:13:37.760 --> 00:13:39.010
Navier-Stokes equation.

00:13:58.200 --> 00:13:59.952
Let me write it down,
to start with.

00:14:03.656 --> 00:14:05.912
Actually, I'll put it on
a separate blackboard.

00:14:09.690 --> 00:14:11.380
So there's our topic.

00:14:11.380 --> 00:14:13.610
So we always know what our
topic is, because it's up

00:14:13.610 --> 00:14:15.990
there, and it's just going
to live there for a bit.

00:14:15.990 --> 00:14:17.740
And in fact, in some
classrooms--

00:14:17.740 --> 00:14:21.220
you can't do it so easily
here, but my favorite

00:14:21.220 --> 00:14:25.240
classroom is 4-265 because it
has pretty much this much

00:14:25.240 --> 00:14:27.810
blackboards in the front, and it
has blackboards all around

00:14:27.810 --> 00:14:29.060
the side, and on the back.

00:14:29.060 --> 00:14:31.450
So I don't use the back ones so
much, but the side ones are

00:14:31.450 --> 00:14:32.750
really, really useful.

00:14:32.750 --> 00:14:35.570
Because you can, for example,
put the topic, like I've done

00:14:35.570 --> 00:14:39.080
here, on the side blackboard,
and just let it stay there the

00:14:39.080 --> 00:14:40.180
entire time.

00:14:40.180 --> 00:14:41.980
You can put an outline
of the lecture.

00:14:41.980 --> 00:14:43.600
OK, so let's say we
have a lecture on

00:14:43.600 --> 00:14:44.750
Navier-Stokes equation.

00:14:44.750 --> 00:14:46.330
We want to look at them,
try to understand them.

00:15:10.010 --> 00:15:12.813
So here are the equation.

00:15:12.813 --> 00:15:16.580
Well "are," "is," the plural
is a bit ambiguous.

00:15:16.580 --> 00:15:19.980
This is actually three
equations, one because it's a

00:15:19.980 --> 00:15:21.980
vector, vector, vector.

00:15:26.690 --> 00:15:30.920
Already there, you see something
that's harder to do

00:15:30.920 --> 00:15:31.990
with slides.

00:15:31.990 --> 00:15:33.880
You'd have to work harder
to do that in slides.

00:15:36.890 --> 00:15:42.450
You can just go back, and
annotate as you go.

00:15:42.450 --> 00:15:46.100
And here, you can see the entire
topic while you're

00:15:46.100 --> 00:15:46.820
looking at this.

00:15:46.820 --> 00:15:50.430
So, for example, the student has
now got overwhelmed by all

00:15:50.430 --> 00:15:52.456
the little symbols here--

00:15:52.456 --> 00:15:57.030
the del squared, the partial
derivative, the v dot grad--

00:15:57.030 --> 00:15:59.820
that part always scared me when
I was a physics student.

00:15:59.820 --> 00:16:04.840
I knew what del dot v is,
but what's v dot del?

00:16:04.840 --> 00:16:06.940
So you get scared by all that.

00:16:06.940 --> 00:16:09.050
And then people forget,
they panic.

00:16:09.050 --> 00:16:11.200
Because their short-term term
memory got filled with every

00:16:11.200 --> 00:16:12.520
single, little, chunk here.

00:16:12.520 --> 00:16:15.080
Their chunks are, remember,
very small.

00:16:15.080 --> 00:16:17.720
And they forgot, what
are they doing?

00:16:17.720 --> 00:16:20.000
Navier-Stokes equation
fluid mechanics.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:20.690
OK.

00:16:20.690 --> 00:16:28.180
And now, you can even improve
that first blackboard by

00:16:28.180 --> 00:16:32.660
talking about, what does
this apply to?

00:16:32.660 --> 00:16:43.845
Drag, turbulence, river
flow, airplanes.

00:16:47.930 --> 00:16:49.270
So here, you can have a

00:16:49.270 --> 00:16:51.070
reminder of why it's important.

00:16:51.070 --> 00:16:53.790
So now that just stays up
there the whole time.

00:16:53.790 --> 00:16:56.370
And people can re-center
themselves every time they get

00:16:56.370 --> 00:16:58.670
confused of what they're
doing, just by that.

00:16:58.670 --> 00:17:00.640
And then, you can continue.

00:17:00.640 --> 00:17:04.220
You can say, OK, let me
try to explain the

00:17:04.220 --> 00:17:05.280
meaning of these terms.

00:17:05.280 --> 00:17:08.000
So let's do the terms
one at a time.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:09.250
What's this?

00:17:16.630 --> 00:17:20.680
So this term here is Dvdt.

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:22.530
We've seen things like that--
that's sort of like an

00:17:22.530 --> 00:17:23.780
acceleration.

00:17:31.370 --> 00:17:34.510
You can annotate the equation
right there.

00:17:34.510 --> 00:17:38.360
That's also hard to
do on a slide.

00:17:38.360 --> 00:17:40.930
I mean, you can do it, you can
work at it, but it's very

00:17:40.930 --> 00:17:42.730
natural on a chalkboard.

00:17:42.730 --> 00:17:45.450
Now, there's some things that
are common to chalkboards and

00:17:45.450 --> 00:17:49.230
slides, which is the
use of color.

00:17:49.230 --> 00:17:51.870
So now this, unfortunately,
is blue, which is

00:17:51.870 --> 00:17:53.466
not the ideal color.

00:17:53.466 --> 00:17:55.860
Unfortunately, I
don't have my--

00:17:55.860 --> 00:17:58.950
orange is generally better,
but anyway I have blue.

00:17:58.950 --> 00:18:01.900
Can you see the blue?

00:18:01.900 --> 00:18:04.530
So marginally?

00:18:04.530 --> 00:18:07.030
Maybe this orange, even though
it's not as big, will be

00:18:07.030 --> 00:18:08.000
better than the blue.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.600
OK, well this shows you an
example of color, and the

00:18:10.600 --> 00:18:12.570
importance of choosing
the right color.

00:18:12.570 --> 00:18:14.200
There used to be a green
one here, but

00:18:14.200 --> 00:18:16.770
they're isn't green anymore.

00:18:16.770 --> 00:18:19.440
Blue is not ideal, I
won't use the blue.

00:18:19.440 --> 00:18:21.610
Let's try this.

00:18:21.610 --> 00:18:23.450
Is that better?

00:18:23.450 --> 00:18:24.200
OK.

00:18:24.200 --> 00:18:27.620
So let me use this orange one,
and I'll try to write large,

00:18:27.620 --> 00:18:29.230
even though it's not as bold.

00:18:29.230 --> 00:18:31.260
OK, so the use of color.

00:18:31.260 --> 00:18:34.710
That's important in both
slides and blackboard.

00:18:34.710 --> 00:18:35.960
What's the use of color here?

00:18:35.960 --> 00:18:38.930
Is it just because it's nice
to have a pretty picture?

00:18:38.930 --> 00:18:39.570
No.

00:18:39.570 --> 00:18:43.000
The reason for using the color
is that you get layering.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:48.030
So again, remember the
students' dilemma.

00:18:48.030 --> 00:18:50.220
Pretty much all students'
dilemma come from the

00:18:50.220 --> 00:18:52.730
following problem, which
is that their

00:18:52.730 --> 00:18:56.250
chunk size is one symbol.

00:18:56.250 --> 00:18:58.180
You've been teaching the
Navier-Stokes equation for 20

00:18:58.180 --> 00:19:01.380
years, your chunk size is
the entire equation.

00:19:01.380 --> 00:19:01.620
Right?

00:19:01.620 --> 00:19:03.170
So that's one chunk to you,
you just write it

00:19:03.170 --> 00:19:04.520
down, like I just did.

00:19:04.520 --> 00:19:06.300
But for the student, every
single, little

00:19:06.300 --> 00:19:07.630
thing is one symbol.

00:19:07.630 --> 00:19:11.340
So now, if you then write all
of this stuff in the same

00:19:11.340 --> 00:19:14.100
color, as your rest of your
equation, it just

00:19:14.100 --> 00:19:14.980
becomes more stuff.

00:19:14.980 --> 00:19:16.220
They don't know how to
separate it into

00:19:16.220 --> 00:19:17.670
two different objects.

00:19:17.670 --> 00:19:21.820
But, if you write your labels in
a different color, it pops

00:19:21.820 --> 00:19:22.840
out in a different layer.

00:19:22.840 --> 00:19:24.720
They know that lives in a
different space, so you're

00:19:24.720 --> 00:19:27.680
already helping them chunk.

00:19:27.680 --> 00:19:28.930
So what is this?

00:19:31.190 --> 00:19:34.290
This is also a change in v.
So it's sort of like an

00:19:34.290 --> 00:19:35.200
acceleration.

00:19:35.200 --> 00:19:36.830
Well, it's part of the
acceleration, actually.

00:19:41.410 --> 00:19:42.970
So this is another
acceleration.

00:19:42.970 --> 00:19:45.780
It's a change in v, but it's a
change in v because you've

00:19:45.780 --> 00:19:47.880
moved to a new place.

00:19:47.880 --> 00:19:50.560
So this is a change in v
because you waited--

00:19:50.560 --> 00:19:51.960
you move to a new time.

00:19:51.960 --> 00:19:54.930
This is a change in v because a
little piece of fluid moved

00:19:54.930 --> 00:19:57.250
to new place, where the fluid
velocity is different.

00:19:57.250 --> 00:19:59.320
So these two things together
are two different

00:19:59.320 --> 00:20:02.710
contributions to the change in
v. So we'll actually call this

00:20:02.710 --> 00:20:14.370
whole thing D of vdt, which is
actually its actual name.

00:20:14.370 --> 00:20:16.560
So this is an acceleration.

00:20:16.560 --> 00:20:20.370
These are the two pieces of it--
this is the acceleration.

00:20:20.370 --> 00:20:23.030
What's on the other side?

00:20:23.030 --> 00:20:26.070
Well, this guy, pressure--

00:20:26.070 --> 00:20:27.420
p is pressure--

00:20:27.420 --> 00:20:28.360
grading of pressure.

00:20:28.360 --> 00:20:29.910
So that's the differences
in pressure.

00:20:29.910 --> 00:20:33.150
So that's going to do some kind
of thing, like a force.

00:20:33.150 --> 00:20:34.580
And row is density.

00:20:34.580 --> 00:20:36.430
So you're taking a force--

00:20:36.430 --> 00:20:42.820
I'll put it in quotes, because
it's not quite a force, it's

00:20:42.820 --> 00:20:44.180
sort of force per area.

00:20:44.180 --> 00:20:53.510
But now you divide by density,
and you get f over m.

00:20:53.510 --> 00:20:55.150
So f over m.

00:20:55.150 --> 00:21:00.860
So we have, here this guy--

00:21:00.860 --> 00:21:06.360
acceleration is equal
to f over m.

00:21:06.360 --> 00:21:09.360
Do you recognize that
equation before?

00:21:09.360 --> 00:21:11.140
Yes, Newton's Second Law.

00:21:11.140 --> 00:21:16.680
So this whole thing, so far
here, is just this is a

00:21:16.680 --> 00:21:17.710
equals f over m.

00:21:17.710 --> 00:21:21.440
So this is the pressure forces,
and this must be the--

00:21:30.550 --> 00:21:32.880
and this is the viscous forces
divided by the mass.

00:21:32.880 --> 00:21:34.740
So these are the two
contributors to the forces--

00:21:34.740 --> 00:21:37.490
pressure forces, viscous
forces--

00:21:37.490 --> 00:21:39.290
and those produce the
acceleration.

00:21:39.290 --> 00:21:43.110
So the Navier-Stokes equation
comes out just as Newton's

00:21:43.110 --> 00:21:45.260
Second Law all over again.

00:21:45.260 --> 00:21:49.220
So now, this kind of drawing
is quite difficult

00:21:49.220 --> 00:21:49.960
to do in the slide.

00:21:49.960 --> 00:21:50.270
Yes.

00:21:50.270 --> 00:21:51.990
AUDIENCE: So I actually
would argue with you.

00:21:51.990 --> 00:21:54.110
You could prepare a set of
slides with annotations, and

00:21:54.110 --> 00:21:55.360
then you could do everything.

00:21:55.360 --> 00:21:57.692
You could put all the
information [INAUDIBLE] in a

00:21:57.692 --> 00:21:59.360
slide, or in multiple slides.

00:21:59.360 --> 00:22:00.860
[INAUDIBLE] animation.

00:22:00.860 --> 00:22:01.120
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:22:01.120 --> 00:22:03.520
So you could put them on
multiple slides, and then flip

00:22:03.520 --> 00:22:06.170
to it, one by one That's true.

00:22:09.650 --> 00:22:11.980
So you can do it, which is
why I said you can do

00:22:11.980 --> 00:22:13.320
it, but it's hard.

00:22:13.320 --> 00:22:15.600
Because it is a bit of a pain,
and you can do it.

00:22:15.600 --> 00:22:20.720
OK but then the problem is, you
want to now leave that on.

00:22:20.720 --> 00:22:24.990
So now you want to have not only
this, but you also want

00:22:24.990 --> 00:22:27.830
to have this, and leave it on
for the entire lecture.

00:22:27.830 --> 00:22:30.610
Because this is the meaning
of the terms.

00:22:30.610 --> 00:22:32.400
And now you're going to leave it
there, and talk about each

00:22:32.400 --> 00:22:33.800
term, one by one.

00:22:33.800 --> 00:22:34.130
Yes

00:22:34.130 --> 00:22:36.754
AUDIENCE: But you could also
give them a handout, with all

00:22:36.754 --> 00:22:38.558
the slides there, so
they would have

00:22:38.558 --> 00:22:39.542
everything in front of them.

00:22:39.542 --> 00:22:42.002
And if they ever want to go
back, they can look back on

00:22:42.002 --> 00:22:44.462
the previous slide.

00:22:44.462 --> 00:22:47.890
[INAUDIBLE] but I think so far
this is not a strong argument

00:22:47.890 --> 00:22:49.342
against the slides.

00:22:49.342 --> 00:22:51.762
Maybe the question's about
interactivity.

00:22:51.762 --> 00:22:53.698
If somebody asks you
a question, what

00:22:53.698 --> 00:22:55.150
about the third term?

00:22:55.150 --> 00:22:57.710
If you don't have a slide
for that, then--

00:22:57.710 --> 00:22:57.980
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:22:57.980 --> 00:23:02.340
And this is the point
I'm coming to.

00:23:02.340 --> 00:23:03.100
So there's that.

00:23:03.100 --> 00:23:05.480
And I agree with you, you can
do this with slides, you can

00:23:05.480 --> 00:23:07.190
give people a handout.

00:23:07.190 --> 00:23:14.020
Though the problem with
the handout--

00:23:14.020 --> 00:23:17.730
suppose you put all of this on
the handout for them, so that

00:23:17.730 --> 00:23:21.160
now, when you erase this screen,
and that screen, you

00:23:21.160 --> 00:23:22.910
go to another thing they
still have something to

00:23:22.910 --> 00:23:24.040
refer back to you.

00:23:24.040 --> 00:23:28.710
The problem is that you want
it all in one visual field.

00:23:28.710 --> 00:23:31.280
And you don't have that when
it's on a handout.

00:23:31.280 --> 00:23:34.770
So you have a problem
of split attention.

00:23:34.770 --> 00:23:38.150
So now the student's attention
is switching between the

00:23:38.150 --> 00:23:40.270
screen, and the handout--

00:23:40.270 --> 00:23:41.300
screen and handout.

00:23:41.300 --> 00:23:45.450
And when they look at the
screen, they're trying to

00:23:45.450 --> 00:23:47.110
remember what they're
confused about.

00:23:47.110 --> 00:23:50.280
And now they look
at the handout.

00:23:50.280 --> 00:23:52.460
This is the analogy.

00:23:52.460 --> 00:23:57.650
When I was in Prague, I would
look at a street sign, and I

00:23:57.650 --> 00:24:00.230
would read the word, and look
at all the letters.

00:24:00.230 --> 00:24:00.860
[INAUDIBLE]

00:24:00.860 --> 00:24:01.940
or something like that.

00:24:01.940 --> 00:24:04.610
And I would look away.

00:24:04.610 --> 00:24:08.420
Two seconds later, I could not
remember more than one letter

00:24:08.420 --> 00:24:10.430
that I saw on the
street sign--

00:24:10.430 --> 00:24:11.170
on the street name.

00:24:11.170 --> 00:24:15.460
The reason is, because each of
the letters was random to me.

00:24:15.460 --> 00:24:18.430
So, yes, someone who's Czech,
just says, oh yeah, that's

00:24:18.430 --> 00:24:19.840
Main Street, of course.

00:24:19.840 --> 00:24:20.520
No big deal.

00:24:20.520 --> 00:24:21.225
What's there to remember?

00:24:21.225 --> 00:24:23.660
It's Main Street, it's
in the Main Square.

00:24:23.660 --> 00:24:26.810
Whereas me, as the foreigner,
has no clue.

00:24:26.810 --> 00:24:28.310
And it's all new data to me.

00:24:28.310 --> 00:24:30.140
So it's the same way
for the students.

00:24:30.140 --> 00:24:31.760
This is all new to them.

00:24:31.760 --> 00:24:33.430
So when they're looking
at something else,

00:24:33.430 --> 00:24:34.900
you're talking about--

00:24:34.900 --> 00:24:36.550
you're going to discuss,
what's the

00:24:36.550 --> 00:24:37.800
dimensions of this term?

00:24:48.740 --> 00:24:51.410
They look at this thing, and now
you have a big analysis of

00:24:51.410 --> 00:24:53.140
the dimensions of this, you
want to check that all the

00:24:53.140 --> 00:24:55.610
dimensions are right, and your
goal is eventually to work out

00:24:55.610 --> 00:24:57.020
the dimensions of this--

00:24:57.020 --> 00:25:00.300
viscosity, let's say.

00:25:00.300 --> 00:25:02.790
They might be frightened
of the partial.

00:25:02.790 --> 00:25:05.750
So they look at this, and they
say, oh, yeah, where does the

00:25:05.750 --> 00:25:07.160
Dvdt come from?

00:25:07.160 --> 00:25:09.100
And then they look back at their
handout, and they've

00:25:09.100 --> 00:25:12.190
already forgotten pretty
much what this was.

00:25:12.190 --> 00:25:14.170
Because they are
the foreigner.

00:25:14.170 --> 00:25:17.580
They are the tourist
in this land.

00:25:17.580 --> 00:25:18.372
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:25:18.372 --> 00:25:21.264
I was just going say that
I would have said

00:25:21.264 --> 00:25:23.674
something very similar.

00:25:23.674 --> 00:25:26.566
The annotation part of it is to
[INAUDIBLE] slides at all,

00:25:26.566 --> 00:25:28.814
because if I was making slides
for this lecture, I would've

00:25:28.814 --> 00:25:29.833
done exactly what you did.

00:25:29.833 --> 00:25:33.850
But it would all be nicely
spaced, and there would be no

00:25:33.850 --> 00:25:35.531
handwriting issues.

00:25:35.531 --> 00:25:37.170
So if anything, slides would
be better for that.

00:25:37.170 --> 00:25:41.565
But I think that the argument
for slides is [INAUDIBLE]

00:25:41.565 --> 00:25:44.340
having them linger on,
but also pacing.

00:25:44.340 --> 00:25:46.544
Like, the fact that it doesn't
flip up so quickly, because

00:25:46.544 --> 00:25:48.249
the [INAUDIBLE] that I've taken
where they use slides

00:25:48.249 --> 00:25:50.684
and use [INAUDIBLE], it goes by
so quickly that you have no

00:25:50.684 --> 00:25:53.119
chance to internalize.

00:25:53.119 --> 00:25:55.885
The fact that you have to write
it out by hand forces

00:25:55.885 --> 00:25:57.970
you to slow down, in a
way that is really

00:25:57.970 --> 00:25:59.100
helpful for the listener.

00:25:59.100 --> 00:26:00.010
And so that's something that's
really important [INAUDIBLE]

00:26:00.010 --> 00:26:01.180
difference.

00:26:01.180 --> 00:26:01.410
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:26:01.410 --> 00:26:03.960
And that's a fundamentally
important point about pacing.

00:26:03.960 --> 00:26:07.130
And this partly addresses
your question about how

00:26:07.130 --> 00:26:08.200
big should you write.

00:26:08.200 --> 00:26:10.340
So one of the reasons for
writing big, is that you're

00:26:10.340 --> 00:26:12.740
writing slower.

00:26:12.740 --> 00:26:15.640
And writing slower, generally
forces your pace to match the

00:26:15.640 --> 00:26:20.610
pace that is absorbable
by the students.

00:26:20.610 --> 00:26:25.040
So I'll come back to that point
in just one second.

00:26:25.040 --> 00:26:29.710
So let me just finish the point
about the visual field.

00:26:29.710 --> 00:26:33.620
The good thing about the
blackboard is, you could call

00:26:33.620 --> 00:26:35.650
it cognitive offloading.

00:26:35.650 --> 00:26:38.610
In one glance, everything
that the students

00:26:38.610 --> 00:26:40.690
need, can be there.

00:26:40.690 --> 00:26:43.090
So they don't really have
to remember much.

00:26:43.090 --> 00:26:46.320
And the short-term memory
isn't overfull.

00:26:46.320 --> 00:26:47.130
They're registers.

00:26:47.130 --> 00:26:49.160
They're a low-register
machine.

00:26:49.160 --> 00:26:52.420
Or rather, they have the same
number of registers as us, but

00:26:52.420 --> 00:26:53.250
they don't store as much

00:26:53.250 --> 00:26:55.530
information in their registers.

00:26:55.530 --> 00:26:58.540
So their registers don't get
overfull, because everything's

00:26:58.540 --> 00:26:59.010
right there.

00:26:59.010 --> 00:27:01.930
Whereas there is a much bigger
danger of register overfilling

00:27:01.930 --> 00:27:03.440
with slides.

00:27:03.440 --> 00:27:05.430
Then, as you point out,
there's the issue of

00:27:05.430 --> 00:27:06.520
interactivity.

00:27:06.520 --> 00:27:11.410
So this is partly a performance
question.

00:27:11.410 --> 00:27:19.160
Slides, not only are they
much more pre-prepared--

00:27:19.160 --> 00:27:21.500
I mean, you can prepare your
blackboards, as well, but you

00:27:21.500 --> 00:27:23.400
actually do have to re-perform
it each time.

00:27:23.400 --> 00:27:25.840
Whereas a slide, as you say, you
just click to Return, or

00:27:25.840 --> 00:27:28.280
Next, and there you are,
at the next slide.

00:27:28.280 --> 00:27:31.460
So there's much less
performance in it.

00:27:31.460 --> 00:27:35.040
And it seems much more
pre-scripted.

00:27:35.040 --> 00:27:38.020
Now, what does that signal
to the students?

00:27:38.020 --> 00:27:39.140
The pre-scripting.

00:27:39.140 --> 00:27:42.360
It says to the students, look,
this is all one, tight thing.

00:27:42.360 --> 00:27:47.390
It's sort of like a play on
a stage, that you're only

00:27:47.390 --> 00:27:50.520
supposed to applaud at
particular times.

00:27:50.520 --> 00:27:51.900
A modern-day play.

00:27:51.900 --> 00:27:54.640
Back in Elizabethan times, in
Shakespeare's time, people

00:27:54.640 --> 00:27:56.980
cheered, and screamed, and
cat-called, and it was a much

00:27:56.980 --> 00:27:58.940
more lively thing
on the stage.

00:27:58.940 --> 00:28:03.500
But now, everyone sits really
quiet, God help you if you

00:28:03.500 --> 00:28:06.820
cough, you try to wait, and you
think about your coughing,

00:28:06.820 --> 00:28:08.500
and then you don't think about
the play, and you try to

00:28:08.500 --> 00:28:09.480
prevent your coughing.

00:28:09.480 --> 00:28:12.650
So all that transfers a bit.

00:28:12.650 --> 00:28:16.830
That same mentality comes when
you're using slides.

00:28:16.830 --> 00:28:19.520
People think, oh my God, this is
a pre-scripted thing-- how

00:28:19.520 --> 00:28:23.230
dare I intervene, and
break into that.

00:28:23.230 --> 00:28:25.690
So if your goal is to encourage
students to

00:28:25.690 --> 00:28:27.950
question, it's harder to
do that with slides.

00:28:27.950 --> 00:28:29.480
You still can do it.

00:28:29.480 --> 00:28:31.470
You can, for example, put
questions on the slides-- and

00:28:31.470 --> 00:28:33.570
you definitely should do that
you're going to use slides--

00:28:33.570 --> 00:28:38.860
but the random, spontaneous
character of your session--

00:28:38.860 --> 00:28:40.390
the good side of that,
is going to be

00:28:40.390 --> 00:28:41.640
minimized by the slides.

00:28:46.220 --> 00:28:49.410
So this one was just to continue
saying, OK, now we're

00:28:49.410 --> 00:28:52.280
going to leave these two on,
and we're going to do the

00:28:52.280 --> 00:28:53.680
dimensions of each term.

00:28:53.680 --> 00:28:58.530
I have one, two, three,
four, let's say--

00:28:58.530 --> 00:29:00.110
four terms I want
to talk about.

00:29:00.110 --> 00:29:03.470
I'll do the dimensions of
two terms on this board,

00:29:03.470 --> 00:29:06.300
dimensions of two terms on that
board, now I'll have all

00:29:06.300 --> 00:29:07.900
the dimensions there.

00:29:07.900 --> 00:29:10.400
And now I can start, for
example, doing dimensional

00:29:10.400 --> 00:29:12.340
analysis on this side
of the room.

00:29:12.340 --> 00:29:16.890
And we'll eventually get to the
Reynolds number, which is

00:29:16.890 --> 00:29:19.490
vr over nu.

00:29:19.490 --> 00:29:21.510
Once we know this guy's
dimensions.

00:29:21.510 --> 00:29:23.810
And v, we know his dimensions,
r the size of

00:29:23.810 --> 00:29:24.880
your sphere or something.

00:29:24.880 --> 00:29:26.540
So this is dimensionless.

00:29:32.490 --> 00:29:35.820
Now you've got the Reynolds
number, you've also got, say,

00:29:35.820 --> 00:29:39.990
drag coefficient, which is
f over 1/2 [INAUDIBLE]

00:29:39.990 --> 00:29:42.620
v squared times some area.

00:29:42.620 --> 00:29:44.480
So this is also dimensionless.

00:29:44.480 --> 00:29:46.780
So now, you have two
dimensionless things.

00:29:46.780 --> 00:29:49.855
And then finally,
the finale is--

00:30:24.530 --> 00:30:27.920
So now, let's say by the end of
the lecture, you get to the

00:30:27.920 --> 00:30:30.510
point where you've plotted
the drag coefficient, a

00:30:30.510 --> 00:30:33.270
dimensionless thing, versus
the Reynolds number, on a

00:30:33.270 --> 00:30:35.710
log-log scale.

00:30:35.710 --> 00:30:38.200
And then you can talk about
this, you can go back and you

00:30:38.200 --> 00:30:39.210
say, OK, well what is this?

00:30:39.210 --> 00:30:40.080
This is really interesting.

00:30:40.080 --> 00:30:41.210
It looks like it was constant.

00:30:41.210 --> 00:30:42.440
And then what happened?

00:30:42.440 --> 00:30:44.150
Well, you can go back
and talk about that.

00:30:44.150 --> 00:30:47.430
And as you talk about it, the
entire graph is visible to

00:30:47.430 --> 00:30:50.720
everyone, as well as the source
of all the pieces of

00:30:50.720 --> 00:30:52.500
the graph, which is all the--

00:30:52.500 --> 00:30:53.770
why is everything
dimensionless?

00:30:53.770 --> 00:30:55.350
Well, you have it on
these two boards.

00:30:55.350 --> 00:30:57.450
And what are the terms
that you used?

00:30:57.450 --> 00:30:58.650
Well, those are all on there.

00:30:58.650 --> 00:31:02.410
So all of that is visible
in one glance.

00:31:02.410 --> 00:31:07.160
So that's an example of
something that is hard to do

00:31:07.160 --> 00:31:08.880
in the slides.

00:31:08.880 --> 00:31:10.985
Now, it's not easy to
get it right on

00:31:10.985 --> 00:31:11.800
the blackboard, either.

00:31:11.800 --> 00:31:13.550
You do have to plan.

00:31:13.550 --> 00:31:15.960
You have to plan by saying,
what am I going

00:31:15.960 --> 00:31:17.670
to put on each board?

00:31:17.670 --> 00:31:19.910
And how am I going to structure
the boards?

00:31:19.910 --> 00:31:23.010
But you can do that on your
lesson plan, for example, on

00:31:23.010 --> 00:31:24.410
the back of the lesson plan.

00:31:24.410 --> 00:31:26.370
Say, OK, how many boards
do I have?

00:31:26.370 --> 00:31:28.000
And what am I going to use?

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:31.830
And then, if you want to take
advantage of the fact that

00:31:31.830 --> 00:31:34.660
everything is visible all the
time, you generally don't want

00:31:34.660 --> 00:31:37.430
to use the up-and-down
nature of the board.

00:31:37.430 --> 00:31:41.670
You just want to use two boards
on each of the regions.

00:31:41.670 --> 00:31:45.750
If you push this up, and start
writing on this guy, you're

00:31:45.750 --> 00:31:47.580
now OK, still.

00:31:47.580 --> 00:31:51.560
But then, when you push this
up, and you write on here,

00:31:51.560 --> 00:31:54.480
you've covered this guy up.

00:31:54.480 --> 00:31:56.620
And yes, you've lost some
of that advantage.

00:31:56.620 --> 00:31:59.520
Again, you can plan it out,
and do a trade off.

00:31:59.520 --> 00:32:03.870
But that is harder to
do with slides.

00:32:03.870 --> 00:32:08.210
Now, your question about how big
you should write so that

00:32:08.210 --> 00:32:11.580
everyone can see, versus telling
the whole story.

00:32:11.580 --> 00:32:14.510
I think it is important to try
to tell the whole story.

00:32:14.510 --> 00:32:17.330
It doesn't have to be the entire
lecture sits on the set

00:32:17.330 --> 00:32:20.610
of blackboards, but a coherent
chunk of the lecture should

00:32:20.610 --> 00:32:21.860
sit on the blackboards.

00:32:23.870 --> 00:32:25.510
You have two things
you could control.

00:32:25.510 --> 00:32:28.990
One you can control is the
writing size, and the other is

00:32:28.990 --> 00:32:30.740
what you write down.

00:32:30.740 --> 00:32:33.450
So this is a similarity
between slides and

00:32:33.450 --> 00:32:36.890
blackboards, which is
you don't want to

00:32:36.890 --> 00:32:39.450
write everything down.

00:32:39.450 --> 00:32:43.540
Because if you write everything
down, then you say,

00:32:43.540 --> 00:32:46.330
well for example, did
I write every single

00:32:46.330 --> 00:32:47.260
thing I said here?

00:32:47.260 --> 00:32:50.410
No, because I want the main
ideas to come across.

00:32:50.410 --> 00:32:52.990
Every little detail that I say,
that should be either in

00:32:52.990 --> 00:32:55.130
the notes, or in some book.

00:32:55.130 --> 00:32:59.660
But the main point should be on
the blackboard at a level

00:32:59.660 --> 00:33:02.880
of detail that people
can absorb.

00:33:02.880 --> 00:33:03.940
It's the same thing
with slides.

00:33:03.940 --> 00:33:05.310
You don't want to put everything
on the slides.

00:33:05.310 --> 00:33:08.230
So, you can still write big,
if you just cut down

00:33:08.230 --> 00:33:10.740
how much you write.

00:33:10.740 --> 00:33:14.270
And generally, that is more
suited to what students need.

00:33:14.270 --> 00:33:19.360
Because, again, they are living
in the dirt of what is

00:33:19.360 --> 00:33:20.960
this, and what is this.

00:33:20.960 --> 00:33:22.830
And you want to try to
bring them up higher.

00:33:22.830 --> 00:33:25.090
So you don't want to spend a
whole bunch of time on all

00:33:25.090 --> 00:33:26.080
these little guys.

00:33:26.080 --> 00:33:28.630
You want to try to bring them
up higher, and put some

00:33:28.630 --> 00:33:31.910
high-level chunks onto the
little bits that they have.

00:33:31.910 --> 00:33:35.580
So use a big chalk, write,
large, just don't write

00:33:35.580 --> 00:33:36.110
everything.

00:33:36.110 --> 00:33:38.840
And try to fit a coherent
piece onto all the

00:33:38.840 --> 00:33:39.410
blackboards.

00:33:39.410 --> 00:33:40.860
It doesn't have to be
a whole lecture.

00:33:40.860 --> 00:33:43.220
Although Feynman, at
Caltech, when he

00:33:43.220 --> 00:33:44.350
gave the Feynman Lectures--

00:33:44.350 --> 00:33:46.220
well, what later became the
Feynman Lectures-- he did

00:33:46.220 --> 00:33:49.620
actually plan it so that he
would start at one corner, and

00:33:49.620 --> 00:33:53.480
he would end all the way here.

00:33:53.480 --> 00:33:57.020
And I find that's too hard to
do if you're also going to

00:33:57.020 --> 00:33:59.530
make the lecture at
all interactive.

00:33:59.530 --> 00:34:01.640
For example, if you're going to
have questions where you're

00:34:01.640 --> 00:34:03.960
going to have the students give
answers, and you're going

00:34:03.960 --> 00:34:04.960
to write down the answers.

00:34:04.960 --> 00:34:06.830
Well, you're not necessarily
going to keep all the answers

00:34:06.830 --> 00:34:08.690
for the rest of the class.

00:34:08.690 --> 00:34:11.630
So the goal of corner-to-corner,
I think, is

00:34:11.630 --> 00:34:12.570
a bit too strict.

00:34:12.570 --> 00:34:15.190
But the general idea is sound.

00:34:15.190 --> 00:34:18.620
Any questions about that before
we take a break, and

00:34:18.620 --> 00:34:22.409
then go onto slides,
and slide design?

00:34:22.409 --> 00:34:23.370
Yes.

00:34:23.370 --> 00:34:26.525
AUDIENCE: I just wanted to
comment that also, a lot of

00:34:26.525 --> 00:34:29.399
students, if there are slides,
and they're available online,

00:34:29.399 --> 00:34:32.280
they will just print them out,
and not come to lectures.

00:34:32.280 --> 00:34:34.699
PROFESSOR: That's true.

00:34:34.699 --> 00:34:37.250
A lot of students will just
print the lecture slides, and

00:34:37.250 --> 00:34:39.510
then just think they can thumb
through them, and understand

00:34:39.510 --> 00:34:40.290
the lecture.

00:34:40.290 --> 00:34:42.820
So that's partly--

00:34:42.820 --> 00:34:48.199
you could call it the
optimism of youth.

00:34:48.199 --> 00:34:51.560
That they don't realize how
much they're actually not

00:34:51.560 --> 00:34:53.810
seeing, because they didn't
actually come.

00:34:53.810 --> 00:34:56.770
They think if they just follow
each slide, they've understood

00:34:56.770 --> 00:34:57.110
everything.

00:34:57.110 --> 00:34:59.770
But there's no way to put
everything in a slide.

00:34:59.770 --> 00:35:03.160
If you packed a slide with
everything you said that was

00:35:03.160 --> 00:35:06.330
worth remembering, or that was
actually part of the structure

00:35:06.330 --> 00:35:08.020
of the argument, then it
would become not a

00:35:08.020 --> 00:35:10.510
slide, but a book chapter.

00:35:10.510 --> 00:35:11.870
And so, yeah.

00:35:11.870 --> 00:35:13.720
I think there is a reasonable
argument that if there's a

00:35:13.720 --> 00:35:16.080
book chapter--

00:35:16.080 --> 00:35:17.930
maybe they don't want to come to
lecture if all you're doing

00:35:17.930 --> 00:35:18.890
is reading the book chapter.

00:35:18.890 --> 00:35:20.705
But slide, and lecture,
are so different.

00:35:20.705 --> 00:35:24.030
It's sort of like, if you just
take a few photographs of the

00:35:24.030 --> 00:35:26.030
blackboard, could you
replace the lecture?

00:35:26.030 --> 00:35:28.520
No, but you're right, students
do think that.

00:35:28.520 --> 00:35:31.810
So actually I don't like giving
them handouts of the

00:35:31.810 --> 00:35:34.410
slides, if I do happen
to use slides.

00:35:34.410 --> 00:35:36.560
Because it's really not a
substitute for a lecture.

00:35:36.560 --> 00:35:39.590
It's an aid to the lecture, just
like the blackboard is an

00:35:39.590 --> 00:35:40.740
aide to the lecture.

00:35:40.740 --> 00:35:43.400
But what's important about the
lecture is, what are you

00:35:43.400 --> 00:35:45.040
having them do in the lecture?

00:35:45.040 --> 00:35:46.730
And that's the reason they
should come into lecture.

00:35:46.730 --> 00:35:48.590
Because in lecture, they're
actually struggling with some

00:35:48.590 --> 00:35:50.290
stuff, and you've structured
it so that they

00:35:50.290 --> 00:35:51.740
struggle, and learn.

00:35:51.740 --> 00:35:54.330
And somehow you have
to convince them

00:35:54.330 --> 00:35:55.750
that that's the value.

00:35:55.750 --> 00:35:59.070
And it's hard, because
of what you say.

00:35:59.070 --> 00:36:00.730
Other comments or questions?

00:36:00.730 --> 00:36:02.228
One second, in the back.

00:36:02.228 --> 00:36:03.722
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:36:03.722 --> 00:36:07.042
But at the same time, I've
probably taken at least half a

00:36:07.042 --> 00:36:09.210
dozen classes where every single
word that the lecturer

00:36:09.210 --> 00:36:12.150
spoke, was present
on the slide.

00:36:12.150 --> 00:36:16.183
And then it felt kind of
worthless going, because you

00:36:16.183 --> 00:36:20.378
show up, you pick up the slide
handouts, and you can read the

00:36:20.378 --> 00:36:22.314
slides during the lecture.

00:36:22.314 --> 00:36:24.129
You pay no attention to the
lecture, because he's not

00:36:24.129 --> 00:36:24.750
saying anything that
isn't there.

00:36:24.750 --> 00:36:25.760
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:36:25.760 --> 00:36:27.780
So that's sort of the worst
of both worlds.

00:36:27.780 --> 00:36:30.820
So now, what they've done, is
they've taken the constraints

00:36:30.820 --> 00:36:32.000
of the slide format--

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:33.710
because there's only so many
words you can put on the

00:36:33.710 --> 00:36:35.990
slide, and make it even
at all readable--

00:36:35.990 --> 00:36:37.750
and often they don't make it
readable, and I'll show you an

00:36:37.750 --> 00:36:40.240
example when we come back.

00:36:40.240 --> 00:36:42.550
And so then they've torqued the
lecture to be basically

00:36:42.550 --> 00:36:44.320
reading out the slide.

00:36:44.320 --> 00:36:46.600
So now they messed up the
lecture, and the slide still

00:36:46.600 --> 00:36:49.580
isn't really a good
substitute.

00:36:49.580 --> 00:36:51.410
It's a huge problem.

00:36:51.410 --> 00:36:54.280
I think the answer to that, is
that if you're going to use

00:36:54.280 --> 00:36:56.790
slides, they're really an aide,
but the students really

00:36:56.790 --> 00:36:59.000
need to learn how to read
a book, or your notes.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:00.480
Or something that's actually
a coherent

00:37:00.480 --> 00:37:02.822
presentation of the material.

00:37:02.822 --> 00:37:03.300
Yes.

00:37:03.300 --> 00:37:05.790
AUDIENCE: So when you write
something on the board to

00:37:05.790 --> 00:37:09.533
respond to a comment, and it
[INAUDIBLE] some of your space

00:37:09.533 --> 00:37:12.620
that you could otherwise use to
plan for the usual stuff.

00:37:12.620 --> 00:37:15.150
So when do you erase
that comment?

00:37:17.670 --> 00:37:19.030
PROFESSOR: That's
a good question.

00:37:19.030 --> 00:37:21.650
So how temporary should
stuff be?

00:37:21.650 --> 00:37:26.920
One way to do it is to think
about the number of minutes

00:37:26.920 --> 00:37:29.280
each thing deserves.

00:37:29.280 --> 00:37:30.490
So that--

00:37:30.490 --> 00:37:33.560
I like things like that to be
on the board the whole time,

00:37:33.560 --> 00:37:35.290
if possible.

00:37:35.290 --> 00:37:38.100
And now it may be that, halfway
through, I might

00:37:38.100 --> 00:37:40.080
reclaim that board if I
don't have a choice.

00:37:40.080 --> 00:37:42.570
But I'd like that to be there
for a while, at least, because

00:37:42.570 --> 00:37:45.250
that's really the main reason
we're doing all this stuff.

00:37:45.250 --> 00:37:46.190
And what are we doing.

00:37:46.190 --> 00:37:48.650
So ideally, I'd put that on the
side blackboard, and just

00:37:48.650 --> 00:37:51.100
leave it there forever.

00:37:51.100 --> 00:37:53.410
Something like this, I would
like it to stay there the

00:37:53.410 --> 00:37:54.920
whole time, so we remember.

00:37:54.920 --> 00:37:56.840
So this, I would
mark as, "don't

00:37:56.840 --> 00:37:59.830
erase," if at all possible.

00:37:59.830 --> 00:38:06.520
So when I'm writing stuff
down, I would know, how

00:38:06.520 --> 00:38:07.840
perishable is the material?

00:38:07.840 --> 00:38:09.920
That's the word I'm
looking for.

00:38:09.920 --> 00:38:12.440
So suppose I ask people
a question,

00:38:12.440 --> 00:38:13.500
like the wood blocks.

00:38:13.500 --> 00:38:15.220
OK, what's the frequency
going to be?

