00:42:32.250 --> 00:42:36.360
And I will erase all this, and
put up a slide that we're

00:42:36.360 --> 00:42:37.410
going to critique.

00:42:37.410 --> 00:42:38.870
And then we'll talk
about technical

00:42:38.870 --> 00:42:40.080
presentations versus teaching.

00:42:40.080 --> 00:42:42.740
Because there's a lot of
misconceptions that come from

00:42:42.740 --> 00:42:44.100
technical presentations.

00:42:44.100 --> 00:42:45.310
And therefore, people
think we should

00:42:45.310 --> 00:42:46.580
use slides for teaching.

00:42:46.580 --> 00:42:49.510
OK, so see in 10 minutes, or
if people have questions

00:42:49.510 --> 00:42:50.760
during the break.

00:42:55.280 --> 00:43:03.950
OK, so our next task is to
figure out, if you are going

00:43:03.950 --> 00:43:07.650
to use slides, what
should you do.

00:43:07.650 --> 00:43:12.880
And related to that point is,
when are slides appropriate.

00:43:12.880 --> 00:43:16.880
People have the idea the slides
are always appropriate

00:43:16.880 --> 00:43:19.440
for teaching, because they
see them used all

00:43:19.440 --> 00:43:22.780
the time for seminars.

00:43:22.780 --> 00:43:25.280
So if you go, and give a talk
at a conference, you go to a

00:43:25.280 --> 00:43:26.380
conference, most--

00:43:26.380 --> 00:43:27.620
almost all the talks--

00:43:27.620 --> 00:43:32.100
or at the department seminars,
basically people now come with

00:43:32.100 --> 00:43:34.690
some form of slides.

00:43:34.690 --> 00:43:36.900
When I was an undergraduate, it
was sort of transitional--

00:43:36.900 --> 00:43:41.670
people came with overhead
projector foils.

00:43:41.670 --> 00:43:44.210
And it was sort of shifting,
from seminars used to be

00:43:44.210 --> 00:43:46.220
blackboard seminars, and then
they shifted to overhead

00:43:46.220 --> 00:43:48.860
projectors, at least
in physics.

00:43:48.860 --> 00:43:51.290
And now it's pretty much slides
all the way through.

00:43:51.290 --> 00:43:56.880
But there's a fundamental
difference between seminar

00:43:56.880 --> 00:43:59.420
presentation, and teaching.

00:43:59.420 --> 00:44:02.220
And seminar presentation--

00:44:02.220 --> 00:44:03.790
basically you're talking
to people

00:44:03.790 --> 00:44:05.240
who are sort of experts.

00:44:05.240 --> 00:44:08.320
They may not be experts in that
particular area you've

00:44:08.320 --> 00:44:09.250
understood.

00:44:09.250 --> 00:44:11.160
Probably not, otherwise they
would have invited one of them

00:44:11.160 --> 00:44:13.150
to talk, instead of you.

00:44:13.150 --> 00:44:16.700
So now, you're the expert
locally, on that local area.

00:44:16.700 --> 00:44:18.500
But in the broader area, you're
talking to basically

00:44:18.500 --> 00:44:19.740
people who are already
interested in, and are

00:44:19.740 --> 00:44:21.120
professionals in the field.

00:44:21.120 --> 00:44:23.985
And maybe some apprentices in
the field, who are going to

00:44:23.985 --> 00:44:26.320
soon be professionals, like
graduate students.

00:44:26.320 --> 00:44:30.550
So your goal is not to slowly,
necessarily, uncover one or

00:44:30.550 --> 00:44:34.430
two ideas, especially if it's
a 10-minute conference

00:44:34.430 --> 00:44:35.970
presentation.

00:44:35.970 --> 00:44:42.000
Your goal is something like,
here are the core, main

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:44.490
ideas-- one or two points-- and
here's something to show

00:44:44.490 --> 00:44:47.430
you that really interesting
stuff is going on.

00:44:47.430 --> 00:44:50.410
And you should pay more
attention to me is part of the

00:44:50.410 --> 00:44:51.920
goal of the seminar.

00:44:51.920 --> 00:44:54.290
Now that's very different
in teaching.

00:44:54.290 --> 00:44:57.570
In teaching, your goal really is
to kindle some new thoughts

00:44:57.570 --> 00:44:58.510
in the student.

00:44:58.510 --> 00:45:03.560
And who are very different
from a seminar audience.

00:45:03.560 --> 00:45:04.570
They are not professionals.

00:45:04.570 --> 00:45:07.910
Maybe they would like to
eventually be, but part of

00:45:07.910 --> 00:45:10.530
your job is to kindle that
interest so they would like to

00:45:10.530 --> 00:45:11.520
become professionals.

00:45:11.520 --> 00:45:14.500
So you have a very, very
different audience, and

00:45:14.500 --> 00:45:17.650
generally much different
time constraint.

00:45:17.650 --> 00:45:20.870
In a seminar, maybe it's 10
minutes, maybe 15 minutes.

00:45:20.870 --> 00:45:23.150
Rarely, once you start getting
well known, maybe you get

00:45:23.150 --> 00:45:24.830
invited to give a 50-minute
seminar.

00:45:24.830 --> 00:45:28.060
But, teaching, you generally
will have 50 minutes.

00:45:28.060 --> 00:45:32.030
So your time is different, your
audience is different.

00:45:32.030 --> 00:45:35.070
So just because slides are used
so much for seminars,

00:45:35.070 --> 00:45:37.130
does not mean they should be
used so much for teaching.

00:45:37.130 --> 00:45:39.990
You should really use them when
you don't really have a

00:45:39.990 --> 00:45:43.570
choice, and when it seems like
it's the optimal thing to do.

00:45:43.570 --> 00:45:46.690
So for example, art
history class.

00:45:46.690 --> 00:45:49.250
Now, an art history class, it
would be fantastic to go to

00:45:49.250 --> 00:45:51.600
Sienna, and look at all the
tapestries, and take the whole

00:45:51.600 --> 00:45:52.950
class with you.

00:45:52.950 --> 00:45:55.470
Now that's just too expensive.

00:45:55.470 --> 00:45:57.430
So, instead, you show slides.

00:45:57.430 --> 00:45:59.215
That's exactly why they're
called slides-- they

00:45:59.215 --> 00:46:01.350
originally were 35 millimeter
slides.

00:46:01.350 --> 00:46:03.610
35 millimeter?

00:46:03.610 --> 00:46:06.100
Yeah, 35 millimeter slides.

00:46:06.100 --> 00:46:08.290
So for something like that,
yes, slides are ideal.

00:46:08.290 --> 00:46:12.020
And drawing the tapestries of
Sienna on the blackboard is

00:46:12.020 --> 00:46:14.840
not even close to showing
the actual pictures.

00:46:14.840 --> 00:46:18.290
So, in that case, 100%
go with slides.

00:46:18.290 --> 00:46:20.820
Other cases generally go towards
blackboards, but there

00:46:20.820 --> 00:46:22.770
are cases where, for example,
there are no blackboards in

00:46:22.770 --> 00:46:24.770
the room, and you have
to teach with slides.

00:46:24.770 --> 00:46:25.950
There's no whiteboard, either.

00:46:25.950 --> 00:46:28.730
Whiteboards are not as good as
blackboards, but they're a

00:46:28.730 --> 00:46:29.690
reasonable substitute.

00:46:29.690 --> 00:46:32.370
But there's neither, and
it's just slides.

00:46:32.370 --> 00:46:33.615
Or, yes--

00:46:33.615 --> 00:46:34.980
AUDIENCE: Why aren't whiteboards
as good as

00:46:34.980 --> 00:46:35.890
blackboards?

00:46:35.890 --> 00:46:42.160
PROFESSOR: I find the markers
always dry out, whereas chalk

00:46:42.160 --> 00:46:43.480
always works.

00:46:43.480 --> 00:46:46.040
So blackboard markers never
quite work as well.

00:46:46.040 --> 00:46:50.200
And the other problem, just
me personally, is that I'm

00:46:50.200 --> 00:46:52.130
sensitive to the chemicals
in them.

00:46:52.130 --> 00:46:54.430
So I eventually just get
a bit dizzy using them.

00:46:57.880 --> 00:46:59.710
So I don't like him
for that reason.

00:46:59.710 --> 00:47:00.840
And there's quite
a few people.

00:47:00.840 --> 00:47:02.920
I'm sort of the canary, so I'm
more sensitive, maybe, than

00:47:02.920 --> 00:47:04.900
many people, because I have
lots of allergies.

00:47:04.900 --> 00:47:07.370
But I think lots of people are
bit sensitive to them.

00:47:07.370 --> 00:47:08.670
But, generally, I find
the markers just

00:47:08.670 --> 00:47:09.470
don't work as well.

00:47:09.470 --> 00:47:14.550
And, also, there's very rare
room has lots of whiteboards.

00:47:14.550 --> 00:47:17.320
Whereas many, many, classrooms
have this many blackboards.

00:47:17.320 --> 00:47:20.550
When they replace them with
whiteboards, usually it'll be

00:47:20.550 --> 00:47:21.900
one whiteboard.

00:47:21.900 --> 00:47:25.330
So then you're back to many of
the disadvantages of slides,

00:47:25.330 --> 00:47:28.780
which is that you can't get
a big field of view.

00:47:28.780 --> 00:47:31.910
But now let's say you are
going to use slides.

00:47:31.910 --> 00:47:33.600
How do we make good slides?

00:47:33.600 --> 00:47:36.320
Well, one way to figure out what
constitutes good slides,

00:47:36.320 --> 00:47:38.770
is to look at what constitutes
bad slides.

00:47:38.770 --> 00:47:43.020
So this, here, is
a horrid slide.

00:47:43.020 --> 00:47:44.620
So what we're going to do is,
I'm going to show you how to

00:47:44.620 --> 00:47:45.470
re-write the slide.

00:47:45.470 --> 00:47:47.180
But first, let's figure out what
are some of the problems

00:47:47.180 --> 00:47:47.920
with this slide.

00:47:47.920 --> 00:47:52.600
So, take a couple minutes
with your neighbors.

00:47:52.600 --> 00:47:54.070
You can all see the slide.

00:47:54.070 --> 00:47:57.970
What are the things that just
don't work about it?

00:47:57.970 --> 00:47:59.430
And there's many.

00:47:59.430 --> 00:48:02.600
It's a very competitive field.

00:48:02.600 --> 00:48:06.180
And I'll write some stuff
down on here.

00:48:06.180 --> 00:48:09.540
By the way, one thing is
that the JIT, that I

00:48:09.540 --> 00:48:11.460
just actually shortened.

00:48:11.460 --> 00:48:14.040
It actually was, "Just
in Time Learning".

00:48:14.040 --> 00:48:16.630
I've just shortened it to
improve the typesetting,

00:48:16.630 --> 00:48:18.500
assuming that the audience
knows what it means.

00:48:18.500 --> 00:48:20.900
So the original slide didn't
have that problem.

00:48:25.240 --> 00:48:30.340
So I see you found
lots of trouble.

00:48:30.340 --> 00:48:34.060
Give me one thing
that's wrong.

00:48:34.060 --> 00:48:34.860
Adrian.

00:48:34.860 --> 00:48:36.410
AUDIENCE: There's no message.

00:48:36.410 --> 00:48:37.660
PROFESSOR: What do you
mean by message?

00:48:39.860 --> 00:48:44.310
AUDIENCE: What is the person
trying to tell you here.

00:48:44.310 --> 00:48:48.090
You have to infer what the
person is trying to tell you

00:48:48.090 --> 00:48:50.222
by analysing it yourself.

00:48:55.140 --> 00:48:56.530
PROFESSOR: OK, no message.

00:48:56.530 --> 00:48:59.650
So, the reader, the viewer,
the student--

00:48:59.650 --> 00:49:02.520
this was actually used in a
class, never mind where, but

00:49:02.520 --> 00:49:04.770
it's not here.

00:49:04.770 --> 00:49:09.310
Yeah, what is the teacher
trying to communicate?

00:49:09.310 --> 00:49:12.740
So Jean-Luc Doumont, if you
saw him during IAP--

00:49:12.740 --> 00:49:17.630
he has a great way of talking
about what's a message, versus

00:49:17.630 --> 00:49:18.870
what's information.

00:49:18.870 --> 00:49:20.120
So the message--

00:49:30.220 --> 00:49:33.360
so information, that's
what that slide has.

00:49:33.360 --> 00:49:34.470
It has lots of information.

00:49:34.470 --> 00:49:47.920
That's the "what." Message
is the "so what."

00:49:47.920 --> 00:49:49.530
His native language
is not English.

00:49:49.530 --> 00:49:51.670
I wish I could come up
with things like

00:49:51.670 --> 00:49:55.000
that in other languages.

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:57.970
I think it's fantastic, because
there's lots of

00:49:57.970 --> 00:50:03.280
"what." Well, 12% said Just
