01:04:55.120 --> 01:04:56.280
concept test.

01:04:56.280 --> 01:04:59.500
You'd make another slide for
the Just in Time learning,

01:04:59.500 --> 01:05:02.260
another one for, do lectures
cover too much material.

01:05:02.260 --> 01:05:03.220
So now you have three.

01:05:03.220 --> 01:05:08.060
And now, basically you want an
overall message of, overall

01:05:08.060 --> 01:05:10.730
these instructional changes
were well liked.

01:05:10.730 --> 01:05:13.130
Then you could have one summary
slide, which just

01:05:13.130 --> 01:05:14.850
lists those three points.

01:05:14.850 --> 01:05:17.410
And with maybe three small pie
charts, to remind people of

01:05:17.410 --> 01:05:19.540
each pie chart, to fit
it all together.

01:05:19.540 --> 01:05:23.210
But to try to pull it out of
that, the people won't

01:05:23.210 --> 01:05:25.800
actually get the
three messages.

01:05:25.800 --> 01:05:28.050
So you have to guide
them towards it.

01:05:28.050 --> 01:05:30.310
Hopefully you can use this for
your seminars as well, not

01:05:30.310 --> 01:05:32.020
just for your teaching.

01:05:32.020 --> 01:05:34.310
This works for teaching,
as well seminars.

01:05:34.310 --> 01:05:36.800
Now, how would you actually put
this into practice, in a

01:05:36.800 --> 01:05:37.860
teaching example?

01:05:37.860 --> 01:05:40.970
So that's what comes up next.

01:05:40.970 --> 01:05:44.500
I'll show you a mathematical
example, which you could do on

01:05:44.500 --> 01:05:48.850
the blackboard, or I sort of
optimized it so you could do

01:05:48.850 --> 01:05:50.250
it on slides too.

01:05:50.250 --> 01:05:52.640
And we can see how that goes.

01:05:52.640 --> 01:05:56.040
OK, so here is just the
comparison, side by side, of

01:05:56.040 --> 01:05:57.770
the two slides.

01:05:57.770 --> 01:05:58.840
Just at a glance.

01:05:58.840 --> 01:06:00.520
I don't actually mean for people
to be able to read the

01:06:00.520 --> 01:06:04.140
words, just to see that one has
enough information that

01:06:04.140 --> 01:06:07.160
you can get a point, but doesn't
overload you, and the

01:06:07.160 --> 01:06:09.770
other is just a rat's nest.

01:06:09.770 --> 01:06:11.950
OK, so then the mathematical
example--

01:06:11.950 --> 01:06:14.000
actually, a statistical
mechanics example as well--

01:06:17.450 --> 01:06:19.880
is the log of n factorial.

01:06:19.880 --> 01:06:21.250
So we're going to approximate
the log of n

01:06:21.250 --> 01:06:24.230
factorial using pictures.

01:06:24.230 --> 01:06:25.780
Now why n factorial?

01:06:25.780 --> 01:06:27.010
Well, what is n factorial?

01:06:27.010 --> 01:06:30.270
5 factorial is 5 times 4 times
3 times 2 times 1.

01:06:30.270 --> 01:06:31.660
Why do we care about it?

01:06:31.660 --> 01:06:33.610
It's the most important function
in statistical

01:06:33.610 --> 01:06:35.620
mechanics when you're
counting objects.

01:06:35.620 --> 01:06:39.200
And it shows up in probability
theory all the time.

01:06:39.200 --> 01:06:41.330
And statistical mechanics
has a lot of

01:06:41.330 --> 01:06:43.090
particles, so the n is big.

01:06:43.090 --> 01:06:45.700
So we'd like to approximate
how big n factorial is,

01:06:45.700 --> 01:06:47.810
because it's so big we
take the logarithm.

01:06:47.810 --> 01:06:49.680
OK, let's see if we can
approximate the logarithm

01:06:49.680 --> 01:06:50.930
using pictures.

01:06:54.630 --> 01:06:59.300
So log of n factorial is the
area of those rectangles.

01:06:59.300 --> 01:07:05.014
You can see rectangle for log
2, log 3, log 4, log 5,

01:07:05.014 --> 01:07:07.010
log 6, and log 7.

01:07:07.010 --> 01:07:14.020
And log of n factorial is just
the sum of all of those.

01:07:14.020 --> 01:07:18.220
Say, 3 factorial is 3 times 2
times 1, so log of 3 factorial

01:07:18.220 --> 01:07:21.932
is log of 3, plus log
of 2, plus log of 1.

01:07:21.932 --> 01:07:24.690
Log of 1 is 0, so all you
have left is those

01:07:24.690 --> 01:07:26.580
rectangles to add up.

01:07:26.580 --> 01:07:28.665
OK, so now let's add them
up, approximately.

01:07:31.370 --> 01:07:35.550
So the area under the curve is
your first approximation.

01:07:35.550 --> 01:07:38.220
So the curve is just log k.

01:07:38.220 --> 01:07:39.070
So let's see what that is.

01:07:39.070 --> 01:07:42.140
Well, OK, that's just the
integral of log k from 1 to n,

01:07:42.140 --> 01:07:44.610
from the lower limit
to the upper limit.

01:07:44.610 --> 01:07:46.880
So that we can just do
symbolically, you get n log n

01:07:46.880 --> 01:07:49.370
minus n plus 1.

01:07:49.370 --> 01:07:50.830
OK, now the error.

01:07:50.830 --> 01:07:52.140
Where does the error
come from?

01:07:52.140 --> 01:07:55.770
Well, it comes from
the protrusions

01:07:55.770 --> 01:07:57.830
beyond the log n curve.

01:08:00.470 --> 01:08:02.780
So there you have
the protrusions.

01:08:02.780 --> 01:08:05.010
so we'd like to add up all
those protrusions.

01:08:05.010 --> 01:08:06.400
Well, how are we going
to do that?

01:08:09.200 --> 01:08:12.080
Each piece is almost
a triangle.

01:08:12.080 --> 01:08:15.720
So let's just straighten out
each little piece of log k

01:08:15.720 --> 01:08:16.974
curve, and make triangles.

01:08:19.660 --> 01:08:23.229
And now, it turns out they're
much easier to add up if you

01:08:23.229 --> 01:08:27.850
double them, and make every
triangle into a rectangle.

01:08:27.850 --> 01:08:30.510
OK, so now I'm going to stop
here, and see if you can

01:08:30.510 --> 01:08:32.600
figure out how to add up
all of those pieces.

01:08:32.600 --> 01:08:36.189
What's the sum of all of
those shaded regions?

01:08:36.189 --> 01:08:37.950
Take a minute and check
with your neighbor.

01:08:41.729 --> 01:08:43.750
OK, when you see it,
raise your hand.

01:08:50.670 --> 01:08:54.060
Find someone around who sees
it, if you haven't seen it,

01:08:54.060 --> 01:08:56.220
and check with them.

01:08:56.220 --> 01:08:57.680
Because it is fun to see.

01:08:57.680 --> 01:08:59.170
I don't want to spoil
it unnecessarily.

01:09:05.520 --> 01:09:06.770
Here's a little hint.

01:09:09.800 --> 01:09:14.029
So what you do, is you hold your
hand at the right page,

01:09:14.029 --> 01:09:16.779
and you whack all of the
rectangles, and they slide

01:09:16.779 --> 01:09:21.510
across, and go psssssh, and
stack, and form the last one.

01:09:21.510 --> 01:09:24.670
So that means the sum of all the
corrections, times 2, is

01:09:24.670 --> 01:09:26.149
the last rectangle.

01:09:26.149 --> 01:09:31.979
So log 7, or log n, is twice
your error, roughly.

01:09:31.979 --> 01:09:34.479
So now you just combine the
integral, which is the piece

01:09:34.479 --> 01:09:38.090
under the curve, with the
approximated protrusion, and

01:09:38.090 --> 01:09:40.910
you get that for log
of n factorial.

01:09:40.910 --> 01:09:41.779
So let's see.

01:09:41.779 --> 01:09:44.689
So that is actually very close
to Stirling's formula.

01:09:44.689 --> 01:09:45.670
Let's see how close it is.

01:09:45.670 --> 01:09:47.399
Well where's the error?

01:09:47.399 --> 01:09:51.130
Well, the error comes from when
we straightened out the

01:09:51.130 --> 01:09:55.550
pieces of the log k curve, and
made triangles instead of the

01:09:55.550 --> 01:09:56.900
funny-shaped region.

01:09:56.900 --> 01:10:00.990
So the error is those shaded
guys, which is not very big.

01:10:00.990 --> 01:10:03.120
And most of the error happens
low down, so if you just

01:10:03.120 --> 01:10:05.640
corrected for that, pretty much
it would all go So here

01:10:05.640 --> 01:10:06.920
is the total error.

01:10:06.920 --> 01:10:08.690
Here's an example.

01:10:08.690 --> 01:10:13.930
The picture method, so we get 7
factorial, gives you 8.594.

01:10:13.930 --> 01:10:18.030
The exact answer for the logs
of 7 factorial, 8.525.

01:10:18.030 --> 01:10:20.390
So it's an error only 0.07.

01:10:20.390 --> 01:10:25.040
So all of this just
adds up to 0.07.

01:10:25.040 --> 01:10:30.480
Which ends up being a 7% error
in seven factorial.

01:10:30.480 --> 01:10:34.730
So the moral of the story is
that pictures can help you

01:10:34.730 --> 01:10:37.830
approximate log of n factorial,
and here is your

01:10:37.830 --> 01:10:40.060
approximation.

01:10:40.060 --> 01:10:42.930
So one of the most important
functions

01:10:42.930 --> 01:10:46.080
in statistical mechanics.

01:10:46.080 --> 01:10:49.840
95% with pictures, and
one tiny integral.

01:10:49.840 --> 01:10:52.820
OK, now.

01:10:52.820 --> 01:10:56.190
That's an example or something
you could do if you wanted to

01:10:56.190 --> 01:10:57.520
teach it using slides.

01:10:57.520 --> 01:10:59.730
You could easily do that on the
blackboard, and normally I

01:10:59.730 --> 01:11:00.780
teach it on the blackboard.

01:11:00.780 --> 01:11:04.220
But I made this as an exercise
for myself to say, OK, well

01:11:04.220 --> 01:11:06.900
suppose I have to teach it with
slides, what would I do?

01:11:06.900 --> 01:11:08.150
And you notice here.

01:11:11.440 --> 01:11:19.590
So when I first drafted it,
this slide was missing.

01:11:19.590 --> 01:11:24.880
And I went from here
to there directly.

01:11:24.880 --> 01:11:27.810
And then I thought,
oh, actually--

01:11:27.810 --> 01:11:29.810
so this is about the
interactivity question--

01:11:29.810 --> 01:11:32.130
oh, actually I'm depriving
people of a chance to think

01:11:32.130 --> 01:11:34.000
about something,
and realize it.

01:11:34.000 --> 01:11:36.290
On the board, it's really
easy to pause.

01:11:36.290 --> 01:11:39.530
You just put the picture
up, and you wait.

01:11:39.530 --> 01:11:40.940
And you say, OK, what
do you think?

01:11:40.940 --> 01:11:42.380
And then you start
drawing stuff.

01:11:42.380 --> 01:11:44.660
So I thought, OK, well you can
actually simulate that on

01:11:44.660 --> 01:11:45.380
slides, too.

01:11:45.380 --> 01:11:48.470
So I put the intervening slide
in there, so that people had a

01:11:48.470 --> 01:11:53.880
chance to stop here, and think
about the result before we

01:11:53.880 --> 01:11:57.620
continued on to the solution,
where it adds

01:11:57.620 --> 01:11:59.930
up to the last guy.

01:11:59.930 --> 01:12:05.800
So that's an example of
basically somewhat interactive

01:12:05.800 --> 01:12:07.510
slide teaching of a
mathematical idea.

01:12:07.510 --> 01:12:07.920
Yes.

01:12:07.920 --> 01:12:11.000
AUDIENCE: So why didn't you
animate a slide [INAUDIBLE]

01:12:11.000 --> 01:12:12.632
with boxes to take advantage?

01:12:12.632 --> 01:12:14.380
PROFESSOR: That's
a good question.

01:12:14.380 --> 01:12:15.230
Why didn't I?

01:12:15.230 --> 01:12:18.740
Actually, because, A, I
didn't think of it,

01:12:18.740 --> 01:12:19.990
but it's a good idea.

01:12:25.780 --> 01:12:27.060
I should have probably
done it.

01:12:27.060 --> 01:12:30.640
The problem is that I'm showing
it as a PDF file,

01:12:30.640 --> 01:12:32.890
rather than through
any program.

01:12:32.890 --> 01:12:35.090
So PDF animations--

01:12:35.090 --> 01:12:37.910
I don't know if PDF has
animations in it.

01:12:37.910 --> 01:12:39.110
It probably doesn't.

01:12:39.110 --> 01:12:40.110
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:12:40.110 --> 01:12:42.510
PROFESSOR: Yes, that's true,
it's sort of against the

01:12:42.510 --> 01:12:45.312
purpose of PDF, which
is a stable format.

01:12:45.312 --> 01:12:46.728
Yes.

01:12:46.728 --> 01:12:48.852
AUDIENCE: I actually thought
this entire presentation was

01:12:48.852 --> 01:12:51.838
really clear, and would be just
as good as if you did it

01:12:51.838 --> 01:12:52.392
on a blackboard.

01:12:52.392 --> 01:12:58.609
Because it was interactive,
slow, had pacing, the suspense

01:12:58.609 --> 01:13:00.517
of having us ask
the questions.

01:13:00.517 --> 01:13:03.598
So I think one of the major
reasons why I would be opposed

01:13:03.598 --> 01:13:06.088
[? to teaching ?] in this way,
is just because it takes you

01:13:06.088 --> 01:13:08.578
more time to create the slide.

01:13:08.578 --> 01:13:10.902
From my own experience, it
takes a long time to make

01:13:10.902 --> 01:13:12.562
really good slides, just
fiddling around with

01:13:12.562 --> 01:13:13.558
[INAUDIBLE].

01:13:13.558 --> 01:13:16.712
So I think if you could spend
all the energy we're spending

01:13:16.712 --> 01:13:18.040
on slides instead
on [INAUDIBLE]--

01:13:18.040 --> 01:13:18.550
PROFESSOR: That's
a good point.

01:13:18.550 --> 01:13:20.036
AUDIENCE: --or whatever,
I think that might be

01:13:20.036 --> 01:13:22.370
[INAUDIBLE].

01:13:22.370 --> 01:13:24.120
PROFESSOR: I think that is
a really good point.

01:13:24.120 --> 01:13:26.400
And I hadn't thought of it until
you mentioned it, but

01:13:26.400 --> 01:13:27.700
you're right.

01:13:27.700 --> 01:13:30.780
It took me a long time to
make the slides right.

01:13:30.780 --> 01:13:34.510
To do slides well, you have to
really think about the visual

01:13:34.510 --> 01:13:36.290
presentation, make everything
visual, you're

01:13:36.290 --> 01:13:39.090
making a lot of diagrams.

01:13:39.090 --> 01:13:40.520
There's all kinds of
little tweaks.

01:13:40.520 --> 01:13:43.370
Like, I made sure that all the
diagrams are exactly the same

01:13:43.370 --> 01:13:45.810
size, so that when you flip from
slide to slide, you don't

01:13:45.810 --> 01:13:47.840
get a shift.

01:13:47.840 --> 01:13:49.770
So all those things, you don't
have to worry about on the

01:13:49.770 --> 01:13:50.550
chalkboard.

01:13:50.550 --> 01:13:53.530
And yes, I would advise people,
just as you do, to

01:13:53.530 --> 01:13:56.380
spend that time thinking about
your teaching, and where

01:13:56.380 --> 01:13:57.980
you're going to put the
interactivity in.

01:13:57.980 --> 01:13:59.070
And do it on the blackboard.

01:13:59.070 --> 01:14:01.230
So this is something where,
with a lot of effort, the

01:14:01.230 --> 01:14:03.750
slide reaches to the level
of the blackboard.

01:14:03.750 --> 01:14:06.320
But with colored chalk, and
lots of blackboard, the

01:14:06.320 --> 01:14:10.200
blackboard is just as
good, and quicker.

01:14:10.200 --> 01:14:13.450
And the blackboard has the
advantage that this could be

01:14:13.450 --> 01:14:15.160
two blackboards in your class.

01:14:15.160 --> 01:14:18.750
Say it's a class about visual
representations, and you have

01:14:18.750 --> 01:14:20.920
two blackboards for
this thing.

01:14:20.920 --> 01:14:23.800
The middle two blackboards for
yet another example, the end

01:14:23.800 --> 01:14:25.240
two blackboards for yet
another example.

01:14:25.240 --> 01:14:26.846
And you have all of
them at once.

01:14:26.846 --> 01:14:27.332
Yes.

01:14:27.332 --> 01:14:32.020
AUDIENCE: Last time I taught a
class where I used all slides,

01:14:32.020 --> 01:14:34.395
and when I put the amount of
time that, things like you put

01:14:34.395 --> 01:14:37.186
into this, to make them all so
they perfectly line up, and

01:14:37.186 --> 01:14:39.270
the animations were really
helpful and everything, just

01:14:39.270 --> 01:14:41.270
creating the slides probably
took half the overall time

01:14:41.270 --> 01:14:43.020
that I put into the class.

01:14:43.020 --> 01:14:45.852
But I think the one advantage
was I was able to use

01:14:45.852 --> 01:14:49.020
printouts of those handouts
as class notes.

01:14:49.020 --> 01:14:50.520
Which I handed out
after the class.

01:14:50.520 --> 01:14:51.520
They didn't have them
during class.

01:14:51.520 --> 01:14:55.280
So that's the only advantage, is
you can reuse all of these

01:14:55.280 --> 01:14:56.430
[INAUDIBLE].

01:14:56.430 --> 01:14:57.520
PROFESSOR: And that's
exactly true.

01:14:57.520 --> 01:15:02.180
So all these nice figures, we
did it for this class, and for

01:15:02.180 --> 01:15:04.250
a seminar on making slides.

01:15:04.250 --> 01:15:07.260
And then I used them verbatim
in my Street-Fighting

01:15:07.260 --> 01:15:08.720
Mathematics textbook.

01:15:08.720 --> 01:15:11.210
So basically, to make good
slides requires making

01:15:11.210 --> 01:15:13.500
something pretty much
publication quality.

01:15:13.500 --> 01:15:15.060
And then, you do have something
publication quality,

01:15:15.060 --> 01:15:17.050
but maybe the first time you
teach it, that's not where you

01:15:17.050 --> 01:15:19.360
want to be spending your time.

