01:21:32.660 --> 01:21:34.245
About slide talks.

01:21:34.245 --> 01:21:37.210
Were there any questions about
slides talks versus teaching,

01:21:37.210 --> 01:21:40.450
versus blackboards.

01:21:40.450 --> 01:21:43.386
So one of the papers says that
the best usage of slides is as

01:21:43.386 --> 01:21:46.510
a completed form that's
understandable without the

01:21:46.510 --> 01:21:49.170
talk that comes with it.

01:21:49.170 --> 01:21:51.380
Is that for a research talk?

01:21:51.380 --> 01:21:53.970
Yes, for a research seminar,
that's what you want.

01:21:53.970 --> 01:21:55.390
You want two channels.

01:21:55.390 --> 01:22:01.340
You want the auditory channel,
and the slide channel, or the

01:22:01.340 --> 01:22:02.515
visual channel--

01:22:02.515 --> 01:22:04.790
whatever's on the blackboard,
however you do it.

01:22:04.790 --> 01:22:08.090
You want them to stand
independently.

01:22:08.090 --> 01:22:12.495
So if people are deaf, and they
just see the slides, they

01:22:12.495 --> 01:22:14.120
get something out of the talk.

01:22:14.120 --> 01:22:16.990
And if they're blind, and they
just hear your speech, they

01:22:16.990 --> 01:22:18.740
get something out of the talk.

01:22:18.740 --> 01:22:22.660
That's, I would say, less
true for teaching.

01:22:22.660 --> 01:22:26.980
The slides tend not to be so,
message, message, message.

01:22:26.980 --> 01:22:31.356
You may develop a point, build
up a bit of suspense, and then

01:22:31.356 --> 01:22:33.488
give a final message.

01:22:33.488 --> 01:22:38.900
So there's more interaction that
happens from the lecture,

01:22:38.900 --> 01:22:40.130
generally, when you're
teaching, than

01:22:40.130 --> 01:22:42.344
in a research seminar.

01:22:42.344 --> 01:22:43.380
So those are somewhat
different.

01:22:43.380 --> 01:22:46.200
But generally, you do want
your slides, or your

01:22:46.200 --> 01:22:50.154
blackboard work, to somehow
stand independently.

01:22:50.154 --> 01:22:52.589
Although I've just violated that
principle right there.

01:22:52.589 --> 01:22:56.972
This is meaningless unless
you've heard what I said.

01:22:56.972 --> 01:22:59.407
But as I said, it's not
an absolute rule.

01:22:59.407 --> 01:23:01.842
It's just that there's
tendencies that are different

01:23:01.842 --> 01:23:04.277
between [INAUDIBLE] talks,
and teaching.

01:23:04.277 --> 01:23:07.502
What do you do if you're
assigned to a classroom with a

01:23:07.502 --> 01:23:08.150
bad blackboard situation.

01:23:08.150 --> 01:23:09.122
In other words, not like this.

01:23:09.122 --> 01:23:11.070
This is fantastic.

01:23:11.070 --> 01:23:13.710
It would be even more ideal if
there was a slide [INAUDIBLE].

01:23:13.710 --> 01:23:17.510
But what do you do if you go
to a classroom with, for

01:23:17.510 --> 01:23:19.928
example, just one whiteboard,
or just one or two

01:23:19.928 --> 01:23:20.916
blackboards?

01:23:20.916 --> 01:23:23.386
Then you have to work harder.

01:23:23.386 --> 01:23:26.844
Then you have to plan even more
carefully, how are you

01:23:26.844 --> 01:23:27.832
going to use the blackboard.

01:23:27.832 --> 01:23:30.302
And be more telegraphic.

01:23:30.302 --> 01:23:33.513
Put coarser details
on the boards, not

01:23:33.513 --> 01:23:34.254
every single detail.

01:23:34.254 --> 01:23:35.736
Use the notes more.

01:23:35.736 --> 01:23:39.194
So you optimize the constraints
that you have.

01:23:42.652 --> 01:23:44.920
Should you only use the front
half of the room.

01:23:44.920 --> 01:23:47.870
Suppose you're in a room which
has blackboards all around.

01:23:47.870 --> 01:23:49.490
Should you only use the front
half of the room?

01:23:49.490 --> 01:23:52.187
Yeah, I generally try to use
only the front half of the

01:23:52.187 --> 01:23:56.042
room, because people can look at
that, and glance out of the

01:23:56.042 --> 01:23:59.280
side of their eye at the side,
and then, the front as well.

01:23:59.280 --> 01:24:02.810
The back forces people to turn
around, so they're much less

01:24:02.810 --> 01:24:03.530
likely to use it.

01:24:03.530 --> 01:24:05.930
So it's sort of like putting
something on the ceiling.

01:24:05.930 --> 01:24:07.370
[INAUDIBLE] never see it.

01:24:07.370 --> 01:24:09.690
So generally, yeah, I use the
front of the room, and

01:24:09.690 --> 01:24:10.940
[INAUDIBLE] the side.

01:24:13.180 --> 01:24:17.359
Should all slides have a "so
what" element, or is that only

01:24:17.359 --> 01:24:18.990
for research talks?

01:24:18.990 --> 01:24:20.770
Definitely for a research talk,
all the slides should

01:24:20.770 --> 01:24:24.260
have a "so what," so people
know what the point is.

01:24:24.260 --> 01:24:27.084
And ideally, for teaching,
you should have two.

01:24:27.084 --> 01:24:30.230
Now, last time, I didn't mention
one of the fundamental

01:24:30.230 --> 01:24:32.420
benefits of putting
a "so what," an

01:24:32.420 --> 01:24:34.380
assertion, in every slide.

01:24:34.380 --> 01:24:35.630
So that was the idea.

01:24:47.120 --> 01:24:50.040
So the slide title is
the "so what.".

01:24:57.040 --> 01:25:01.040
And then here is the evidence,
maybe a picture, or a graph.

01:25:01.040 --> 01:25:02.540
Some kind of, ideally
visual, evidence.

01:25:02.540 --> 01:25:04.540
So what's the advantage
of doing that?

01:25:04.540 --> 01:25:05.945
It's not just for
the audience--

01:25:05.945 --> 01:25:07.540
it's for you, as well.

01:25:07.540 --> 01:25:10.750
What you do, after you make your
series of slides, with

01:25:10.750 --> 01:25:15.445
your sentences, your "so what."
You extract just the

01:25:15.445 --> 01:25:19.180
sentences, which is easy to do
if you're using a program

01:25:19.180 --> 01:25:20.176
[? like Tech. ?]

01:25:20.176 --> 01:25:22.168
You just [INAUDIBLE],
just the titles.

01:25:22.168 --> 01:25:23.164
However you do it.

01:25:23.164 --> 01:25:24.658
You make a list of sentences.

01:25:30.136 --> 01:25:34.006
And then you see whether
the sentences flow.

01:25:34.006 --> 01:25:37.742
With a sentence, you can tell,
very well, because whether

01:25:37.742 --> 01:25:40.442
your presentation, your
teaching, your seminar is well

01:25:40.442 --> 01:25:43.143
organized, if it herks and
jerks, if sentence one and

01:25:43.143 --> 01:25:45.107
sentence two seem to have
nothing to do with each other,

01:25:45.107 --> 01:25:48.360
there's no transition between
them, well, maybe you need a

01:25:48.360 --> 01:25:51.548
sentence one and a half, a slide
that goes in between.

01:25:51.548 --> 01:25:54.038
Or maybe sentence two belongs
down here, next to something

01:25:54.038 --> 01:25:55.034
that relates better.

01:25:55.034 --> 01:25:59.018
So you can see not just at the
level of the individual

01:25:59.018 --> 01:26:02.006
slides, but at the level of
the entire presentation,

01:26:02.006 --> 01:26:04.994
whether there's a thread
that goes through.

01:26:04.994 --> 01:26:07.680
And if you remember, one of
the principles of good

01:26:07.680 --> 01:26:09.650
teaching is having
a good story.

01:26:09.650 --> 01:26:11.808
So this helps you make
a good story.

01:26:25.030 --> 01:26:27.670
When you're teaching a class
that has expectations for

01:26:27.670 --> 01:26:30.850
teaching lots of material, how
do you reconcile your desire

01:26:30.850 --> 01:26:32.912
to teach the important things
really well, and keep a

01:26:32.912 --> 01:26:34.790
reasonable pace?

01:26:34.790 --> 01:26:38.390
Some things aren't really
reconcilable.

01:26:38.390 --> 01:26:41.190
Classes that, for example, say,
OK, we're going to go

01:26:41.190 --> 01:26:44.180
through the 1,600-page textbook,
