01:30:10.855 --> 01:30:12.340
Actually, I disagree.

01:30:12.340 --> 01:30:17.140
This is a case of start-up
costs, versus running costs.

01:30:17.140 --> 01:30:19.800
So there's many examples
of that, here at issue.

01:30:22.800 --> 01:30:24.800
It's actually a general
principle worth knowing,

01:30:24.800 --> 01:30:26.300
because you can analyze
lots of stuff.

01:30:39.800 --> 01:30:43.770
Another example of this
principle is, suppose you see

01:30:43.770 --> 01:30:47.030
a book that you really like,
that's available in print,

01:30:47.030 --> 01:30:50.516
from publisher n, and there's
also a PDF file online.

01:30:50.516 --> 01:30:53.020
Well, you could just print it
out and replace your printer.

01:30:53.020 --> 01:30:55.510
Or, you could buy the thing
from the publisher.

01:30:55.510 --> 01:30:58.486
Now, unless the publisher's a
total thief -- unfortunately,

01:30:58.486 --> 01:31:01.485
many of them are, but many
of them aren't--

01:31:01.485 --> 01:31:05.672
it's usually much better to
buy it at the bookstore,

01:31:05.672 --> 01:31:09.249
because it's much cheaper, than
to print it on your laser

01:31:09.249 --> 01:31:11.634
printer, get all the paper
trimmed to the right size, and

01:31:11.634 --> 01:31:12.830
have it all bound.

01:31:12.830 --> 01:31:17.070
So the running cost for you to
do one book-- you have no

01:31:17.070 --> 01:31:20.830
start-up cost, you just do it.

01:31:20.830 --> 01:31:24.004
There's no fixed amount you
have to pay, no matter how

01:31:24.004 --> 01:31:25.144
many books you do.

01:31:25.144 --> 01:31:27.272
But there's a running cost,
and your running cost is

01:31:27.272 --> 01:31:28.340
pretty high.

01:31:28.340 --> 01:31:31.930
Whereas the publisher, they
have a big start-up cost.

01:31:31.930 --> 01:31:34.850
What they do, is they make all
these plates, they take them

01:31:34.850 --> 01:31:36.675
to a PDF file, [INAUDIBLE],
they make all these metal

01:31:36.675 --> 01:31:39.240
plates, and they ink
the metal plates,

01:31:39.240 --> 01:31:41.270
stamp it onto the paper.

01:31:41.270 --> 01:31:42.550
So they do all that.

01:31:42.550 --> 01:31:43.482
That's a big start-up cost.

01:31:43.482 --> 01:31:46.168
But their running cost
is much lower.

01:31:46.168 --> 01:31:49.310
They're much more efficient
printing, per book.

01:31:49.310 --> 01:31:51.166
But it requires all that
start-up cost.

01:31:51.166 --> 01:31:55.150
So there's a contrast between
book publishers and you.

01:31:55.150 --> 01:31:58.900
So it's the same thing,
actually, with doing

01:31:58.900 --> 01:31:59.780
[? Tech, ?]

01:31:59.780 --> 01:32:03.030
versus doing, say, regular
word processing.

01:32:03.030 --> 01:32:06.400
With [? Tech, ?] there's
a lot of start-up cost.

01:32:06.400 --> 01:32:08.280
No doubt about that.

01:32:08.280 --> 01:32:09.920
It's not what most people
are used to, you end up

01:32:09.920 --> 01:32:12.180
programming your documents.

01:32:12.180 --> 01:32:14.704
And so, if you're only making
one document, if you only

01:32:14.704 --> 01:32:18.522
write one letter in your life,
no question it's faster to

01:32:18.522 --> 01:32:19.690
write the letter.

01:32:19.690 --> 01:32:22.690
Your have lower running costs.

01:32:22.690 --> 01:32:24.894
You don't have to worry about
the start-up costs if you

01:32:24.894 --> 01:32:27.329
write it using a word
processing program--

01:32:27.329 --> 01:32:29.764
Open Office, for example.

01:32:29.764 --> 01:32:32.810
You just type, and you make it
look like you want, and just

01:32:32.810 --> 01:32:33.420
spit it out.

01:32:33.420 --> 01:32:37.412
But, if you have to write 50
letters that all have a

01:32:37.412 --> 01:32:39.380
roughly similar format,
it's much

01:32:39.380 --> 01:32:40.820
better to get the template.

01:32:40.820 --> 01:32:43.826
You pay the start-up cost once,
learn [? Tech, ?] learn

01:32:43.826 --> 01:32:45.950
some kind of program template.

01:32:45.950 --> 01:32:51.533
And then, you just enter the
blanks into the template.

01:32:51.533 --> 01:32:53.780
The text, dear who, the
address, and all that.

01:32:53.780 --> 01:32:54.940
[INAUDIBLE]

01:32:54.940 --> 01:32:57.550
formatting, that's all
dealt with once.

01:32:57.550 --> 01:33:00.892
So you pay start-up costs,
in return for

01:33:00.892 --> 01:33:01.874
lower running costs.

01:33:01.874 --> 01:33:03.838
And that's basically true
of lectures, too.

01:33:03.838 --> 01:33:06.293
Once you have all your templates
ready, it's much

01:33:06.293 --> 01:33:08.748
faster to do everything
[? in Tech, ?] or in some kind

01:33:08.748 --> 01:33:12.676
of programming, text-processing
system, rather

01:33:12.676 --> 01:33:15.131
than in a word processor.

